<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Removal of Trade Barriers Between Zimbabwe, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 20 (Xinhua) -- There is need for both
Zimbabwe and Mozambique to remove barriers to trade and
investment if the proposed development of the Beira corridor is
to economically benefit countries in the southern Africa region.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of the Beira Corridor Group (BCG) David
Zausmer today said the development corridor, one formalized
toward the end of this year, would provide a mechanism which
encouraged an increase in trade and investment throughout the
corridor.
</P>
<P>
But to achieve success, he said, there is need to remove
factors which hamper the free movement of people, trade and
investment between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Zausmer cited visa requirements for travellers, high tarrifs
along the corridor and lengthy procedures in approval of cross
border investment.
</P>
<P>
He said one of the first tasks of the committees established
as part of the development corridor would be to look at the
barriers to trade and investment between the two countries and
recommend appropriate steps to remove them.
</P>
<P>
''The time is now ripe for both governments and the business
sectors to further accelerate their efforts in developing the
corridor, lest we surrender the opportunity to more powerful
economies in the region,'' Zausmer said in apparent reference to
South Africa currently investing along the corridor.
</P>
<P>
The current Beira corridor is a railway and road network
running between the Zimbabwean eastern border town of Murare to
the Mozambican port city of Beira. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
