<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberian President Visits S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President
Charles Taylor will arrive in South Africa tonight for a private
visit, Foreign Ministry spokesman Marco Boni confirmed this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here from Liberia's capital
Monrovia, Taylor's Information Minister Joe Mulbah has said
Taylor would see President Nelson Mandela during the five-day
visit.
</P>
<P>
But Mandela's spokesman Parks Mankahlana said today that he
was not aware of any such plans.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi
represented Mandela on August 23 at the inauguration in Monrovia
of Taylor as president.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration followed multi-party elections in Liberia in
July in which Taylor received a 75 percent majority.
</P>
<P>
Liberia had before the poll been racked by a six-and-half
years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Liberia enjoy diplomatic relations but do not
have residential missions in each other's capitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
