<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Youths Sexually Misbehaving: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Family planning research in
Zimbabwe shows that more than 60 percent of the country's four
million youths do not take precautions when engaging in sexual
activity.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Mines, Environment and Tourism Minister
Simon Moyo, when he officially launched the Zimbabwe National Family
Planning Council promotion of youth responsibility campaign in
Matabeleland South province today.
</P>
<P>
''While half of young men and one quarter of women aged between 15
to 24 years were sexually active, only 39 percent males and 29
percent females took precautions against sexually transmitted
infections and unwanted pregnancies,'' said Moyo.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the irresponsibility to lack of information which he
hoped would be corrected by the six-month campaign being carried out
all over the country.
</P>
<P>
''Among adolescents aged 15 to 19, nearly half of all births
are unintended. Data from the National AIDS Coordination Program
indicates that 36 percent of reported AIDS cases were from people
infected during adolescent years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign aims to increase awareness and knowledge of
reproductive health issues including associated illnesses, reduce
high risk sexual behavior, reduce pregnancy rates among women
between 10 and 24 years and increase support from policy makers.
</P>
<P>
Moyo called on health personnel, teachers and parents to
complement each other in the effort to educate the youth in
responsible sexual behavior. 
</P>
</TEXT>
