<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Faction Team Visits Breakaway Somaliland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Hussein Mohamed Aidid sent
his deputy president, Abdurahman Ahmed Ali Tuur, to visit
Hargeisa for the first time in four years today, for talks with
the breakaway Republic of Somaliland about a federal system.
</P>
<P>
The delegation with more than 100 people including several of
Hussein Aidid's cabinet ministers were welcomed by a cheering crowd
in Hargeisa, capital of Somaliland.
</P>
<P>
According to sources in Hargeisa, Tuur and his delegation will
open talks with self proclaimed president of Somaliland, Mohamed
Hagi Ibtahim Egal about their political views later today.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Tuur is expected to raise and lobby for a
federal system for the country, an issue less likely to be
accepted by Egal and his supporters.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is of great importance and it has
been sympathized by communities in Somaliland and the supporters
of Hussein Aidid here in Mogadishu with each side looking forward
to hearing from the outcome of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Six parliament members from the self-appointed government of
Egal have already expressed their support to the federal system
raised by Tuur.
</P>
<P>
The idea is also supported by the majority of the Garhajis
subclan which Tuur belongs to.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the two men was proposed by the sultan of
the Garhajis subclan and it was largely welcomed by the Habar
Awal subclan of Egal.
</P>
<P>
Tuur, the first president of Somaliland who announced the
secession of the northwestern regions of Somalia from the rest of
the country during his incumbency in Somaliland in May 1991, took
up arms after the communities of Somaliland elected Egal as
their president.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 people were believed to have died in the bitter
armed confrontations between the two sides in the main towns of
Hargeisa, Buro and many other villages from late 1994 till early
1996.
</P>
<P>
The crowd that welcomed Tuur and his delegation in Hargeisa
today were also divided in two groups, one calling Tuur to join
the administration of Egal for a lasting peace in Somaliland and
the other wishing him success in his federalism endeavors.
</P>
<P>
The two men last met in May 1993. They both belong to the
Issak tribe, one of the four major tribes of Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
