<HEADLINE> Iran Launches First Tehran-Jeddah Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Iran today launched the first
flight between Iranian capital Tehran and Jeddah, a port city in
Western Saudi Arabia, since the 1979 Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Shafti, Managing Director of Iran's National Flag
Carrier Homa, said that the air service is running weekly
between Iran and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
He described the opening of the new air route between Tehran
and Jeddah as a means of further expansion of commercial
relations between the two Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the air route should be considered as one of
the suitable means through which Iranian and Saudi Arabian
businessmen can expand their cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The regular flights on Saturdays would provide an easy way
for Iranian businessmen and those who collect visa directly from
the Saudi Embassy to travel to Saudi Arabia for pilgrimage to
the holy sanctuaries or for meeting their relatives.
</P>
<P>
Based on a protocol signed between the two countries in March,
the Saudi airlines will launch a weekly flight to Tehran according
to a timetable to be announced soon, Shafti said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that with the increase in the number of
these flights Homa would be able to increase its flights to
different cities in Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
