<HEADLINE> Objective Reports Urged on Cameroun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 20 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official
of Cameroun has called on public and private press to safeguard
the interest of the country by reporting objectively.
</P>
<P>
Augustin Kontchou Kouomegni, government spokesman and the
Minister of State in charge of Communication, made the statement
to the press on Friday afternoon at the nation's Television
Production Center in Yaounde.
</P>
<P>
The minister reviewed that Cameroun has been a target of a
smearing campaign aimed at disturbing and tarnishing the image of
the country.
</P>
<P>
He blasted some foreign media organizations, claiming that
some foreign radios, televisions and print media agencies are
encouraging hatred and war in Cameroun.
</P>
<P>
The minister also blamed the Amnesty International on
attacking Cameroun's human rights records unjustly.
</P>
<P>
The minister accused Cameroun's three opposition parties, the
Social Democratic Front, the National Union for Democracy and
Progress and the Cameroun Democratic Union of calling for
violence.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that their reasons for calling for a boycott of
the upcoming presidential election and violence were weak and
dishonest.
</P>
<P>
Election cannot be postponed as requested by the opposition in
parliament, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister emphasized the government's commitment to
democratization process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
