<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Sends Fresh Warning to Turkey over Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Greece today once again warned
Turkey that Athens would support Cyprus in the event of any
aggressive action by Turkey against the island.
</P>
<P>
"Greece will come to Cyprus' aid in the event of any aggressive
action by Ankara," Prime Minister Costas Simitis told the ruling
socialist Pasok party central committee today.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and Turkey could not be normalized
without a just solution to the Cyprus problem, he said, adding
that Cyprus' entry into the European Union (EU) was "a matter of
top priority for Greece."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Madrid communique signed by the two countries
in July fully responded to the conditions outlined by Greece
regarding Greek-Turkish relations, but he stressed that its
reconfirmation needed acts.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Simitis warned Turkey that any change of
the existing status quo in Cyprus by Turkey would mean war for
Athens.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pro- Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the southern part of the island, the Cyprus
Republic, has been ruled by the Greek-Cypriots while the northern
part by the Turkish-Cypriots which declared in 1983 a breakaway
state "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Cameroun's Parties Gear Up for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 20 (Xinhua) -- With 27 days to go for the
October 12 presidential election in Cameroun, various political
parties have geared up for the contest.
</P>
<P>
Feverish political meetings, rallies and consultations are
being held across the nation to sensitize militants and garner
support for the election.
</P>
<P>
So far, 16 candidates have deposited their files for the
upcoming presidential election to the Ministry of Territorial
Administration for screening, including incumbent President Paul
Biya who represents the ruling Cameroun People's Democratic
Movement (CPDM) party.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Territorial Administration started screening
application files on September 18. Ten files have been received
by the ministry and the other six files were said to be
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun now has about 140 political parties. They are all
preparing for the upcoming election. Some parties presented their
own candidates while some plan to boycott the election.
</P>
<P>
There are still some political organizations that have decided
not to present their own candidates, but have already declared
support for President Biya's candidature.
</P>
<P>
These include the National Alliance for Democracy and Progress
(NADP), the National Union for the Total Independence of Cameroun
(UNITOC), the Cameroun National Party (NPA) and the Union for the
Republic (UPR) which comprises 15 political parties.
</P>
<P>
The Cameroun People's Union (UPC-Kodock Faction) has also
resolved to give full support to President Biya's candidature to
the presidency. But the UPC-N Faction has nominated Hogbe Nblend
as its presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Still within the context of the October 12 presidential
election, Samuel Eboua, one of the candidates and leader of the
Movement for Democracy and Progress (MDP) representing a
coalition of 12 political parties, also held a press conference
two days ago to drum up support for his candidature.
</P>
<P>
However, the three major opposition political parties -- the
Social Democratic Front (SDF), the National Union for Democracy
and Progress (NUDP) and the Cameroun Democratic Union (CDU) --
announced their boycott of the upcoming presidential election.
</P>
<P>
They held press conferences and signed a joint declaration,
urging all political parties in the country to fight for what
they called "genuine change and freedom."
</P>
<P>
They also called on the international community to show their
concern and support them in the struggle.
</P>
<P>
Anxiety is mounting among various political parties as well as
their nominees as they are waiting for the publication of the
final list of qualified candidates.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the provisions of the law, the final list
of qualified candidates should be made known on September 22, 20
days before the polling day.
</P>
<P>
Although the 15-day campaigns for the election will officially
begin on September 27, various political parties are continuing
their efforts to realize their ambitions, no matter to win or to
boycott the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
