<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Means Looked For to Speed Repatriation of Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) is taking new measures to
speed the repatriation of Congloese refugees from Tanzania,
according to a news dispatch from Kigoma reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR has commissioned the Tanzania Railways Corporation
(TRC) to look into the possibility of using the southern
Congolese port of Baraka to disembark the returnees to meet the
challenge of the mounting pressure for repatriating the bulk of
22,000 Congolese refugees who have volunteered to go home.
</P>
<P>
The head of the UNHCR sub-office at Uvira in Congo (K),
Micheal Phelps, was quoted as saying that the U.N. refugees
agency would like to utilize the Baraka port on Lake Tanganyika
because 80 percent of the Congolese returnees are from Fizi
district which has Baraka as its nearest anchoring place.
</P>
<P>
Refugees returning to Fizi district are at the moment
disembarking at Kalundu port in Uvira and then transported in
trucks on a pot-holed road to the southern villages for up to a
six-hour drive, according to Phelps.
</P>
<P>
Phelps said that his agency has contacted the marine
department of the TRC in Kigoma to go to Baraka port to inspect
the harboring facility with the intention to build a docketing
facility to enable Tanzanian passenger ships to disembark the
Congolese refugees.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian marine officials are expected to arrive at Baraka
next week to start inspection and make recommendations on
improving the port to the Congolese government and UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR has repatriated 1,666 out of 22,000 Congolese refugees
who have opted to return home from camps in Kigoma Region of
western Tanzania since the start of the repatriation exercise
early this months.
</P>
<P>
The number of refugees to be repatriated is expected to
increase by the end of this month from 600 a week to 3,000 once
UNHCR gets a second leased boat from the TRC to ferry the
returnees three or four times a week, according to the acting
head of the UNHCR sub-office in Kigoma, Luc Stevens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Shortage Warned in N. Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Non-governmental organizations
and the National Disaster Management Organization of Ghana have
warned about an imminent food shortage in the Northern and Upper
East regions of the country due to erratic rainfall.
</P>
<P>
Their warning given at Tamale in northern Ghana is based on a
survey on food security carried out in the two regions in May and
August, according to a Ghana News Agency report reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
"The report painted a gloomy picture of the food security
situation and said the two regions will need about 2,000 tons of
grains to support the worst affected home," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the prolonged drought has had serious
repercussions on the performance of early millet in the upper
east region.
</P>
<P>
The early millet usually blunts the acute food shortage until
the main staples mature, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report cited the case at Adaboya in the Upper East Region
where the villagers have started having raw millet for breakfast
and lunch while others feed on green shea nuts and baobab fruits.
</P>
<P>
"These are all abnormal situations, giving definite
indications of an approaching famine in the area," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Regional Coordinating Council has constituted a
committee to work out strategies to respond to the looming
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
