<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Cancels Water Deal With UK Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The authorities of the Federal
Capital Territory (FCT), where the Nigerian capital Abuja is
located, have decided not to hand over the management of the
newly created Abuja Water Company to Bi-water, a British company.
</P>
<P>
The contract was terminated in compliance with a directive
from the federal government, which said the move was fraught with
a lot of dangers for the country, the News Agency of Nigeria
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Abuja Water Company, set up in July, is mandated to handle
the treatment and distribution of water in the capital in
addition to the collection of water bills.
</P>
<P>
It is also asked to take over the management of all the water
treatment plants owned by the FCT Water Board.
</P>
<P>
A source at the board was quoted by the report as saying today
that the federal government issued the directive for the
revocation of the contract following complaints from some
Nigerians that allowing a foreign firm to handle such simple job
was not in the interest of the country.
</P>
<P>
The federal government also felt convinced that the move, if
not cancelled, would lead to job losses as the FCT Water Board
would be scrapped and its workers laid-off, the source said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency, some labor unions were
among those that petitioned the presidency over the controversial
contract whose details were yet to be made public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
