<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Protesters Clash with Police in East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian protesters
clashed with Israeli police today during a demonstration in the
disputed Ras Al-Amud neighborhood in East Jerusalem to
protest the Jewish presence there.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of Palestinian protesters blocked the road to the Arab
neighborhood with stones and cabbage containers. They threw
stones at Israeli police who fired rubber bullets to disperse
them. But no casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, another group of Palestinian protesters held a
peaceful demonstration in Ras Al-Amud, where 15 Jews occupied two
houses last Sunday sparking a crisis in the already tense
situation between Israel and the Palestinians. The demonstrators
held banners calling on Jews to leave the neighborhood to save
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Under a compromise agreement Thursday between the Israeli
government and American billionaire businessman Irving Moscowitz,
who purchased the houses in Ras Al-Amud in an attempt to build a
Jewish settlement, the 15 settlers would leave the houses to be
replaced by a religious seminar.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has blasted the
agreement as a "trick" to legalize the Jewish presence in the Arab
neighborhood and demanded all Jews leave there.
</P>
<P>
Israeli major opposition parties and peace activists all
criticized the government's agreement with the settlers and asked
the settlers to evacuate the houses in order to avoid an outbreak
of violence.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem has been at the center of the Israeli-Palestinian
dispute and under the Oslo accords, its final status should be
settled through the final-status talks. Israel has claimed the
whole holy city as its eternal and indivisible capital, while
the PNA hopes to create a Palestinian state with the occupied
East Jerusalem as its capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
