<HEADLINE> Team Canada to Visit Latin America in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien said today he will lead the fourth Team Canada mission to
four Latin American countries from January 11 to 23 next year.
</P>
<P>
The mission to Mexico, Brazil, Argentina and Chile will
generate new business for Canadian companies, which are expected
to complete and sign numerous contracts and agreements, according
to a news release from Chretien's office.
</P>
<P>
Chretien will be joined by provincial premiers and territorial
leaders on the mission, his second to the region, as well as by a
delegation of several hundred of business people.
</P>
<P>
"Keeping up our momentum in these dynamic, growing economies of
Latin America will have economic benefits for all regions of
Canada," Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
It is vitally important to consolidate Canada's impressive
gains in this region, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Canadian companies already benefit from our free trade
agreements with Mexico and Chile, and Canada is discussing closer
links with the nations of the Mercosur trade group, which includes
Brazil and Argentina," he added.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Chretien will discuss how to forge closer
economic and political ties with the region in the months
preceding the Summit of the Americas in Santiago, Chile, where
participants plan to launch negotiations on the Free Trade Area of
the Americas.
</P>
<P>
Team Canada is expected to focus on nine priority sectors,
including telecommunications and information technology,
transportation, specialized services, the environment, energy and
natural resources, according to the release.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, two-way merchandise trade between Canada and the four
Latin American countries totaled 11.0 billion dollars (7.9
billion USD), up 62 percent over the 1993 figure.
</P>
<P>
Total Canadian foreign direct investment in the four countries
now exceeds 14 billion dollars (10 billion USD).
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, Chretien has led three Team Canada missions abroad.
</P>
<P>
These missions have led to business deals estimated at over 20
billion dollars (14.4 billion USD), and have opened doors for
Canadian businesses to important contacts and opportunities.
</P>
</TEXT>
