<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Stresses Test Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton Saturday said he would veto any Republican legislation
that does not include standards for testing reading and
mathematics skills.
</P>
<P>
"I'll have to give it the failing grade it deserves, and I'll
veto it," Clinton said in his weekly radio address. "We all know
we have to do more to improve the quality of public education."
</P>
<P>
Republicans fired back. "I think the president is telling
parents and teachers, `I don't trust you,'" Republican Senator
Slade Gorton said in the Republican radio response. "Apparently,
he prefers a system that has Washington, D.C., deciding what's
best for school children in Chehalis, Washington, New York City
and every place in between."
</P>
<P>
Clinton is scheduled to announce 40 million dollars in grants
for charter schools during a visit to the San Carlos Learning
Center in California, one of the country's first such schools.
Education Secretary Richard Riley said more than 420 charter
schools nationwide receive federal support.
</P>
<P>
"Charter schools are established by educators with less red
tape, but higher expectations," Clinton said. "This is an
innovation we cannot afford to lose."
</P>
<P>
Charter schools -- public schools run under contract by
teachers, parents or community leaders -- are a part of Clinton's
education strategy.
</P>
<P>
The president's education plan also establishes testing
standards for fourth-grade reading and eighth-grade math.
Conservatives oppose the idea, arguing that it creates an avenue
for federal control of local schools.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Clinton described testing standards as a way to
"ensure that no child leaves our schools without mastering the
basics."
</P>
<P>
He said he would veto if Congress passes "partisan legislation
that denies our children high national standards or weakens our
national commitment to stronger schools."
</P>
<P>
The House rejected such testing earlier this week in voting
down spending bills to carry the Education, Labor and Health and
Human Services departments through the 1998 budget year. The
Senate approved its version of the spending bills last week, after
attaching Gorton's amendment to convert many education programs
into block grants to states.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
