<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The 14th meeting of the
Angolan-Zambian Mixed Commission of Defense and Security ended
today, urging Angola's opposition UNITA movement to strictly
observe U.N. Security Council's resolution on Angola's peace
process.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued here at the end of the three-day meeting
which started on Thursday called on members of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) and other countries to
support the UN Security Council's resolution banning any
assistance to the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The meeting also urged the Angolan government to continue its
efforts for the full implementation of the Lusaka peace accord
signed in 1994 in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides considered the current state
of the bilateral ties as excellent, and decided to work harder to
promote its further development.
</P>
<P>
Defense ministers of the two countries attended the meeting
and they decided that the 15th mixed meeting be held in Lusaka,
Zambia next year. 
</P>
