<HEADLINE> Egypt Opposes Convocation of Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 20 (Xinhua) -- In a clear-cut language perhaps
for the first time, a senior Egyptian official today expressed
opposition to the convocation of the Middle East and North Africa
Economic (MENA) Conference due to be held in Qatari capital Doha.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt does not wish the conference would be held in a sisterly
Arab country like Qatar and then fail," Osama el-Baz, presidential
advisor for political affairs, told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
It will be "detrimental rather than beneficial" to convene
the conference under current circumstances, he said, adding that
the optimism over peace that prevailed the MENA conference held
in Cairo last November is now regrettably missing in the region.
</P>
<P>
As a direct spinoff of the Mideast peace process, the annual
MENA conference had been held in Casablanca, Morocco; Amman,
Jordan; and Cairo, Egypt since 1994. But peace prospects have been
largely deteriorated since then.
</P>
<P>
Most Arab countries have threatened to boycott the Doha
conference due to Israel's participation, while Qatar insists on
going ahead as scheduled in November.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Syria flatly rejected the conference to
protest Israel's policies against the peace process, while Egypt
has said that its participation hinges on progress on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a meeting held on the sidelines of the 108th
session of the Arab League foregin ministers council which opened
here today, Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Ben Jassem Al-Thani
painted a bleak picture for the economic forum.
</P>
<P>
He said it can not be "as successful as expected" unless Israel
changes its current policy and the peace process makes tangible
progress.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli practice proved that it has failed to implement
its obligations and commitments to the peace process," he said,
adding that Qatar will keep up consultations with other Arab
countries on the peace development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
