<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Vow to Implement Party Congress Policies (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang's comments on the primary stage of socialism have also
received a good response from people in the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, according to the Regional Power Administration
officials. They concluded that the primary stage of socialism
reflects the real conditions of the region, which is rich in coal
and water resources, but lacks funds and technology.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia should improve its power industry based on the
principle of "Three Favorables" and the market, they said.
</P>
<P>
In better-developed areas like the city of Shanghai and Jiangsu
Province, economic affairs officials said they will break down all
barriers in stepping up reforms and opening wider to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
"We cadres in charge of economic administration should
emancipate our minds further and support any kinds of public
ownership," said Xu Zhiyi, director of the Shanghai Municipal
Economic Commission.
</P>
<P>
The decision of the Congress to advance enterprise
restructuring has greatly encouraged officials in charge of
restructuring and those working in state companies.
</P>
<P>
Liu Zhixiang, deputy director of the Regional Commission for
Economic Restructuring of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region,
said that the Congress's decision has made them more confident
about invigorating state-owned enterprises in the region.
</P>
<P>
Most of these are small and Xinjiang should make improving them
an important part of local economic reforms through ideological
emancipation, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Guo Yuhui, deputy chief economist of Beijing's Yanshan
Petrochemical Industry Group Co. Ltd., said that Jiang's report
has provided clear guidelines for the restructuring of state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Deng Tong, a displaced factory worker in Guiyang, the capital
of Guizhou Province, explains that she learned to use computers
after being laid off from the factory and has found a new job, and
concluded, "We should try to improve our own quality, so as to
meet the requirements of the market economy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
