<HEADLINE> Chinese People Vow to Implement Party Congress Policies (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) ended on September 18, and the
Chinese have expressed their determination to implement the
policies that came out of it.
</P>
<P>
They share the same view about stepping up reforms, opening up
wider, and scoring sustained, healthy economic development based
on China's national conditions and the principle of the "Three
Favorables".
</P>
<P>
"The 15th Party Congress's emphasis on the theory of the
primary stage of socialism shows that the Party has a clear
understanding of the country's national conditons and its historic
mission," commented Hu Zhide, the former president of Lanzhou
University in the capital of Gansu province.
</P>
<P>
Gansu is an underdeveloped area, and such poor areas need
ideological emancipation and boldness in intensifying the reforms,
he told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In a discussion in Yunnan province in southwest China, Liu
Shusheng, chairman of the Provincial Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference, said that since the
beginning of China's reforms and opening-up in 1979, Yunnan has
developed on the basis of its own conditions, and has become a
major tobacco, sugar, tea and rubber producer in China.
</P>
<P>
In Changchun, the capital of Jilin Province, Huang Zhenshan,
chairman of the Changchun Changling Group, a state-owned machine
manufacturer, told Xinhua about the company's achievements since
it began issuing stocks in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring has allowed workers to participate in
managing the enterprise, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
