<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Conditions on Joining Unity Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition Labor
Party leader Ehud Barak today put forward his condition of joining
a national unity government on dramatic policy change by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
After discussing with Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani
and lawmaker Yehuda Harel on the issue, Barak said that he would
be willing to consider joining a unity government if Netanyahu
were to shift his policy concerning the Middle East peace process
by 180 degrees.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that if Netanyahu changes his policy... perhaps
there will be something to discuss," Barak told Army Radio.
</P>
<P>
Both Kahalani and Harel are from the Third Way Party, which
joins the coalition government led by the Likud.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani, who is initiating a new campaign to support setting
up a unity government, said there is basis to continue the
discussion and that he intends to propose the idea to the Likud
coalition.
</P>
<P>
The idea of creating a broad-based unity government was first
put forward after Netanyahu's victory in last year's elections and
has been resurrected in the wake of the recent terror attacks in
Jerusalem, which pushed the peace process into deep crisis.
</P>
<P>
During a television speech following the September 4 suicide
bombings in Jerusalem, Harel said a unity government was
"inevitable", and that the only question is whether it will be
formed before or after "the next disaster."
</P>
<P>
The initiative of the Third Way Party for a unity government
has prompted a flurry of reactions. Likud's Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai said today he does not think that the government
has reached the point necessitating the creation of a national
unity government.
</P>
<P>
But Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi, one of Netanyahu's close
supporters, noted in an interview with Israel Radio Saturday night
that Netanyahu and Barak could reach agreement on major issues
about the peace process and that they have ways to discuss the
establishment of a unity government even before an official
invitation for such a move is issued.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that a Labor-Likud coalition now appears
more possible than it seemed immediately following Netanyahu's
rise to power in June last year, considering that Netanyahu has
since then dealt with the Palestinian National Authority and its
president Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Netanyahu's talk this year of an "Allon-Plus" deal
on a permanent settlement between Israel and the Palestinians
signaled a break from traditional Likud dogma on territorial
compromise, and brought him at least theoretically closer to
Barak's views.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians collapsed in
March when Israel broke ground for a Jewish settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem. The crisis deepened following two terror attacks
in July and September and the latest dispute over Jewish presence
in the Ras Al-Amud Arab neighborhood in East Jerusalem, which the
Palestinians want as the capital of a future state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
