<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shell Tops World's Transnational Companies: UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Dutch/Shell group
topped the list of the 100 biggest transnational corporations
(TNCs) for the fifth running year, the United Nations reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The company, merged by the Royal Dutch and the Shell in 1907
and has two separate headquarters in Britain and the Netherlands,
owns almost 80 billion U.S. dollars of foreign assets in 1995,
leading the world's multinational firms, the U.N. Conference on
Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said today in its 1997 edition of
the world investment report.
</P>
<P>
The second to tenth biggest conglomerates are the Ford Motor
Company, the General Electric Company, the Exxon Corporation,
General Motors, Volkswagen AG, IBM, the Toyota Motor Corporation,
Nestle SA and the Mitsubishi Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The 100 multinational giants has 1.7 trillion dollars of assets
in their foreign affiliates, representing about a fifth of the
world's total foreign assets, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Their foreign sales amounted to 2 trillion dollars and their
employment totalled 6 million persons.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, the United States and Japan are home to 87
of the 100 leading TNCs and controlled 88 percent of their foreign
assets. In 1996, the triad accounted for around 90 percent of both
inflows and outflows of developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Australia, Canada and Switzerland have also emerged as
significant overseas investors and investment recipients, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Only two companies from developing countries came into the top
100 list, the Daewoo Corporation and Petroleos de Venezuela SA,
ranking respectively 52nd and 88th. It is the first time
developing countries' companies have entered the list.
</P>
<P>
There are about 44,000 TNCs with about 280,000 overseas
affiliates in the world, the report said. The top 100 companies
mainly invested in construction, food and beverages, chemicals and
pharmaceuticals, petroleum and mining, electronics, automotive,
and metals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
