<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: IMF's Interim Committee Meeting Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippe Maystadt, chairman
of the Interim Committee of the Board of Governors of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), said today the one-day meeting
of his committee was successful and fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Experts here also said that the closed-door meeting is
important in outlining topics for the upcoming annual meetings of
the World Bank and IMF scheduled for September 23-25 in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference later, Maystadt said the
committee "welcomed the agreement reached by the Executive Board
of the IMF" on the quota issue and urged it to "submit before the
end of this year a proposed resolution for the approval of the
Board of Governors to effect the agreed increases in quotas."
</P>
<P>
The present total of IMF quotas would be increased by 45
percent, according to a communique issued at the end of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
It said 75 percent of the overall increase would be distributed
in proportion to present quotas, 15 percent distributed in
proportion to members' shares in calculated quotas (based on 1994
data) and the remaining 10 percent distributed among those members
whose present quotas are out of line with their positions in the
world economy.
</P>
<P>
The last 10 percent of the overall increase includes the one
percent that would be distributed among five members whose current
quotas are far out of line with their relative economic positions,
and which are in a position to contribute to the IMF's liquidity
over the medium term, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
Maystadt told reporters that the committee also "welcomed the
agreement reached by the Executive Board on an amendment of the
IMF's Articles to provide all members with an equitable share of
cumulative SDR (Special Drawing Rights) allocations through a
special one-time SDR allocation amounting to SDR 21.4 billion,
which will double the amount of SDRs already allocated."
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the committee has recommended the
adoption by the Board of Governors of a proposed resolution
concerning the issue.
</P>
<P>
The committee "welcomed the recent progress made in the
implementation of the HIPC (Heavily Indebted Poor Countries)
Initiative, including the decision of the Executive Boards of the
IMF and the World Bank to provide assistance" to several
countries, Maystadt said.
</P>
<P>
He said recent disturbances in Asian financial markets had
again underscored the importance for policy makers in all
countries to ensure the internal consistency of macroeconomic
policies, strengthen financial systems, and avoid excessive
external deficits and reliance on short-term foreign borrowing.
</P>
<P>
As to the lessons to be drawn from the financial disturbances,
the committee stressed the importance of openness and
accountability of economic policy making and of improvements in
financial systems.
</P>
<P>
"Private capital flows have become much more important to the
international monetary system," it said, stressing the need to
make further efforts to "establish a multilateral and
nondiscriminatory system for promoting the liberalization of
capital movements."
</P>
<P>
According to participants at the meeting, the committee, while
noting the generally favorable prospects for the continued
expansion of world output and trade, also stressed that there are
risks confronting individual countries and affecting the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
"In the advanced economies as a group, growth with low
inflation is projected to continue. However, sustained fiscal
consolidation remains a challenge for many countries, requiring
resolute policies over the near and medium term," the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
"The growth performance and prospects of developing countries
as a group have strengthened in recent years. However, further
improvements are needed in many cases to achieve significant
reduction in poverty," it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that in some emerging market economies,
large external imbalances and fragile banking systems have
adversely affected investor confidence and exacerbated the risks
emanating from volatile capital movements.
</P>
<P>
In the transition countries, growth has resumed following good
progress, in most cases, with macroeconomic stabilization and
structural reforms, the communique said. "To safeguard and build
upon the achievements thus far, inflation will in most cases need
to be lowered further through disciplined macroeconomic policies."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
