<HEADLINE> Automobile Sales Chain Opens In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 21 (Xinhua) -- China's first automobile
sales chain opened recently in Changzhou, an industrial city in
Jiangsu province, meaning an interesting development in a country
where chainstores are still relatively new.
</P>
<P>
The outlet in the Changzhou Department Store belongs to
Beijing's Yafei Automobile Chain, which plans to open 22 outlets
nationwide within two months.
</P>
<P>
They will have unified management, creating a unique company,
says Guo Jiyuan, Yafei's president. He says the company has
agreements with 14 auto manufacturers, including Shanghai's
Volkswagen, and he believes that it will get a big market share by
providing various kinds of competitively-priced cars, as well as
good service.
</P>
<P>
It is a breakthrough in car marketing in China, says Xu
Huazhong, director of the Market Circulation Department of the
State Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
This form of management started in China in mid-1980s, and saw
rapid growth. It is now being used in retail sales, the fast food
business, and other service sectors.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese are showing great interest in private cars. A study
of Beijing's Municipal Statistics Bureau shows that 7,500 cars
were sold in the Asian Games Village auto market, the city's
largest, in the first quarter of this year, 82 percent of which
were purchased by individuals.
</P>
<P>
The auto industry grew rapidly over the past few
years. Statistics show that China produced 1.5 million cars in
1995, and 1.8 million last year, including nearly 400,000
sedans. Zhao Fengwu, director of the Market Supervision Department
of the State Administration for Industry and Commerce, predicts
that with the economic growth, China will become one of the
biggest private car markets in the world.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
