<HEADLINE> Arab CNN-Style TV Station to be Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September (Xinhua) -- A London-based satellite TV
channel called the Arab News Network (ANN), which is to be styled
on U.S. Cable News Network (CNN)'s format of news reporting, is
due to be launched next month.
</P>
<P>
The ANN will have hourly bulletins covering breaking news,
current affairs, business, sport and culture, as well as
live talk shows, documentaries and fashion programs, local
newspaper the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the paper published today, Samar Assad,
27, nephew of Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, and chairman of the
ANN, said that ANN will fill the large niche that exists in the
Arabic-language TV market for a fully independent news channel to
serve the 250 million Arabs.
</P>
<P>
"We are independent, both financially and editorially," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Assad noted that "there is huge potential for a neutral TV
channel. We are going to be showing both sides of every story,
even the Arab-Israel story."
</P>
<P>
He said that news from the Arab world will represent about 80
percent of the news coverage, with 20 percent given to
international events.
</P>
<P>
The news will be gathered by correspondents based in
Beirut, Cairo, Amman and Jerusalem as well as roving reporters
in other parts of the region.
</P>
<P>
The station's funding has come from "private investors" based
in Lebanon and the Gulf, Assad said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he denied that there is any involvement of his
uncle in the ANN. 
</P>
</TEXT>
