<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Zimbabwe-World Bank Relations at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has recently
decided to postpone the disbursement of 720 million Zimbabwe
Dollars (62.5 million U.S. Dollars) balance of payments support
to Zimbabwe, bringing once again bilateral relations to a
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The bank is holding back the money because there has been no
satisfactory resolution so far to Zimbabwe's war veterans
payments, according to David Cook, resident representative of the
World Bank in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The move comes hardly a month after it informed the Zimbabwean
government that on the basis of good fiscal management
performance in the 1996/97 financial year which saw the out-turn
for the budget deficit dropping to a surprise 7.1 percent of the
Gross Domestic Product (GDP), it would release the balance of
payments support held up since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The 720 million pending balance of payments support was first
suspended in 1995 after Zimbabwe was accused of missing agreed
economic targets under first phase of reforms (1991-95). The
World Bank, the International Monetary Fund and other donors
wanted Zimbabwe to cut its budget deficit to at least five
percent of its GDP.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, the Zimbabwean government gave in to pressure
from former freedom fighters to resolve their plight and
announced that all the ex-combatants would get a tax-free 50,000
Zimbabwe Dollars (4,300 U.S. Dollars) lump sum pension to be
followed up by a monthly payment of 2,000 Zimbabwe Dollars (173
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
President Robert Mugabe announced that the 50,000 dollars
would be paid before the end of this year while the 2,000 dollars
monthly payments would start in January next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Zimbabwe-World Bank Relations at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 21 (Xinhua) -- However, the compensation
payments to an estimated 70,000 ex-fighters meant that
substantial additional expenditures were likely to be incurred.
Such expenditures had not been provided for in the 1997/98 budget
submitted to parliament last July.
</P>
<P>
Economists estimated that the payments could drain up over
three billion Zimbabwe Dollars a year, which in essence,
represents over five percent of the government's total annual
expenditure. This would push up the budget deficit from around
8.9 percent anticipated for the period to December 1998 to over
12 percent.
</P>
<P>
"It's serious matter because the amounts involved are quite
large and the issue needs to be resolved speedily," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
After the World Bank's decision was announced, most Zimbabwean
people expressed shock and disappointment.
</P>
<P>
Jane Mutssa, President of Indigenous Business Women's
Organisation noted that the World Bank had expressed its wish to
assist Zimbabwe. But now "the bank is punishing the country."
She charged that the bank wanted to cause friction between the
government and its people.
</P>
<P>
Ben Mucheche, President of the Business Development Centre,
strongly suspected that the World Bank wanted to see conflict
between the government and the combatants, adding the bank should
understand the imperative of maintaining political stability for
future economic progress.
</P>
<P>
Affirmative Action Group President Phillip Chiyangwa said,
"The bank should have been sensitive that the Zimbabwean
government's handling of the war veterans' issue was only to
avoid civil disorder and plunging the state into anarchy."
</P>
<P>
In the past months, the ex-fighters had held demonstrations
which at times turned violent against the government demanding
paying their pensions.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Minister of Industry and Commerce Nathan
Shamuyarira said Saturday the bank had sought clarification on
how Zimbabwe intended to finance the recently announced pensions
for ex-combatants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
