<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Calls for Liberalization of Capital Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) stressed here today that an open and liberal system
governing capital movements will enhance economic welfare and
prosperity worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's decision-making body, the Interim Committee, said in
a communique issued at the end of a one-day closed-door meeting
that it has adopted the statement on "The Liberalization of
Capital Movements Under an Amendment of the Fund's Articles."
</P>
<P>
"An amendment of the Fund's Articles will provide the most
effective means of promoting an orderly liberalization of capital
movements consistent with the Fund's role in the international
monetary system," the communique said.
</P>
<P>
Considering that a number of developing countries may come
under speculative attacks after opening their capital account, the
committee stressed that the liberalization must be supported by
sound macroeconomic policies and strong financial systems in
member countries.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after the meeting, Philippe Maystadt,
chairman of the Interim Committee, also said the liberalization of
capital movements should proceed in an orderly, step-by-step way.
</P>
<P>
The Interim Committee has asked the Executive Board of the IMF
to give high priority to completing its work on the liberalization
of capital movements and submitting a report and a proposed draft
amendment to the Board of Governors, according to the communique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
