<HEADLINE> SAARC Meeting on Women Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Technical Committee on
Women in Development of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) began its 12th meeting here today to discuss
the role of women in socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
Twenty high-level officials in charge of women development
affairs from Nepal, India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Bhutan
and the Maldives, the seven member countries of the SAARC, are
participating in the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is to discuss the policy guidelines on women
development issues adopted by the 11th summit of the SAARC in the
Maldives and how these can be put into practice, Nepal's official
news agency RSS said.
</P>
<P>
At the 11th summit, the SAARC leaders resolved to raise
education and literacy rates among women and pledged to coordinate
their efforts and take effective measures to address the problem
of trafficking in women and children in the region so as to bring
women into the mainstream of socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also review the women development programs
being implemented in the region and work out future programs, the
RSS said.
</P>
<P>
K. C. Namgyel, director of the SAARC Technical Committee on
Women in Development, said women of the SAARC countries still lag
far behind in terms of development because of illiteracy, the RSS
said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that common policies and approach should be
adopted to change the situation.  
</P>
