<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Warns GCC Against Hike in Imports Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) has warned its partners in the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) against hiking tariffs on imports as required in a proposed
regional customs union.
</P>
<P>
UAE Higher Customs Council Chairman Obaid Buset said his
country has presented a memorandum outlining its views towards
the proposed single tariff system for the six-member GCC, said the
latest issue of UAE business weekly Emirates Today.
</P>
<P>
"The UAE has presented a memorandum (to GCC) saying that
raising the tariff would increase prices of goods and this will
hurt consumers," Buset said in an exclusive interview with the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
He also said a four-year transitional period proposed by the
GCC for adopting a common customs tariff is not sufficient. But
UAE will respect the measure if enforced, he added.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states, which are Bahrain, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the
UAE, Qatar and Oman, have been discussing the joint customs tariff
for years in effort to create a common Gulf market.
</P>
<P>
The customs project has been hampered by differences on the
level of the tariff as some members are opposed to high duties.
</P>
<P>
GCC officials have finished classification of most products to
be taxed and a decision on the proposed tariff is awaiting
approval by the GCC heads of state. They have spoken of a
compromise on a common tariff of between eight and 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The UAE imposes the lowest tariffs in the 16-year-old Gulf
alliance although it has quadrupled duties on most imports to
four percent. Bahrain, which has little oil, says low duties
would hit its economy as most of its income comes from
import tariffs and taxes.
</P>
<P>
A common GCC market could create one of the biggest markets in
the world, with annual imports of more than 50 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bloc is also the dominant oil power, controlling nearly
45 percent of the global proven crude reserves and producing
around one fifth of world oil output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0066 </DOCNO>
