<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Monetary Authority Chief on Asian Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Given the great diversities
of the economies in Asia, regional monetary cooperation must be
allowed to take shape gradually and in a flexible way, Chief
Executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority Joseph Yam said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Asia seemed to be slow in promoting regional monetary
cooperation in the past, Yam told a lecture sponsored by the Per
Jacobsson Foundation.
</P>
<P>
But things have changed recently, spurred by the Mexican
financial crisis which also affected the region and by the Thai
currency crisis which is right in the middle of the region, he
told hundreds of economists, business executives and officials
from around the world who are here to attend the World Bank/IMF
annual meetings to be held on September 23-25.
</P>
<P>
People must bear in mind two points when adopting an approach
towards Asian monetary cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
First is that Asian monetary cooperation must be considered
within the context of global monetary cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"In other words, we should not, and I believe we are not trying
to, build Fortress Asia" which is not in the best interests of
Asia, Yam said.
</P>
<P>
The second point is that given the great diversity of the
economies in the region, being at very different stages of
financial development, "Asian monetary cooperation should proceed
with flexibility and at a pace comfortable to those wishing to
take part in it," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Realistically, Asian monetary cooperation should be pursued
under "a multi-currency environment", compared with the single
currency monetary union adopted by Europe, Yam pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that monetary cooperation be built and links be
established "first at the bilateral level" between those who are
ready and willing. These bilateral linkages would serve to set
targets and standards for others in the region who are not quite
ready.
</P>
<P>
When the majority of the bilateral linkages have been
established eventually, "we would then have a network, an Asian
monetary network, of considerable strength, which would hopefully
enable Asian monetary problems to be tackled effectively," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"It should also be a network that is capable of being linked up
with monetary systems outside the region, with a view to building
the global monetary framework," Yam said.
</P>
<P>
He listed five areas for Asian monetary cooperation --
information exchange, resource provision, market infrastructure
development, banking supervision and financial regulation, and
policy consultations.
</P>
<P>
"In the Asian pragmatic and patient way, and using the wise
words of the late (Chinese leader) Deng Xiaoping, we cross the
river by groping the stones," Yam said. He said he was confident a
robust and efficient Asian monetary network would be built to
contribute to the financial stability and economic prosperity in
Asia and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
Turning to Hong Kong, Yam said: "as you can see for yourself,
with goodwill and cooperation, the prosperity of Hong Kong has
been ensured" both before and after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will continue to play its role as an international
financial center, and will work hand in hand with all central
banks around the world to build a safer and more robust
international monetary system, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Per Jacobsson Foundation was created in 1964 in honor of
Per Jacobsson, the third Managing Director of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF). It is the first time for the lecture to be
held in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
