<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missiles to be Deployed in Cyprus: Russian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian Ambassador to Cyprus
has said that his country will ensure the Russian-made
surface-to-air missile system S-300, purchased by the Cyprus
government, be deployed in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published here today in Greek Daily
Fileleftheros, Georgi Mouratov dismissed Turkish threats to attack
the island if the S-300 missiles are installed.
</P>
<P>
Mouratov said the contract signed between the government and
Russia for the purchase of the S-300 " concerns our bilateral
relations with the Republic of Cyprus".
</P>
<P>
"Nobody can intervene and violate international law,
threatening with the use of violence, or imposing views relating
to Russia's relations with third countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mouratov said Russia will ensure that the system be
deployed and dismissed Turkish threats to attack the island as
"more of a war of nerves, made to impress".
</P>
<P>
He clarified that the S-300, ordered by the Cyprus
government, is mainly a radar that will enable the Republic to
control flights within its air space.
</P>
<P>
"Statements that Cyprus will be able to attack Turkish
planes over Turkish territory are ridiculous," Mouratov stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also said that only a small number of Russian people
will need to come to Cyprus for a short period in order to
install the anti-aircraft system.
</P>
<P>
The Russian diplomat said his country wants to have close
the friendly relations with Turkey, but said it must be
understood Russia does not allow any country to intervene in its
internal issues.
</P>
<P>
Mouratov's statement came following Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz's threats of possible military measures to counter
the arrival in Cyprus of the S-300 missile system.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz was quoted as saying that deployment of the missiles
"directly threatens Turkey's security". Turkey could not "remain
indifferent in the face of this possibility", he added.
</P>
<P>
Greek Premier Costas Simitis has denounced Yilmaz's statement,
saying Greece would honor its joint defense pact with Cyprus
and would not allow Turkish threats to become reality.
</P>
<P>
But no Cypriot government official has so far come out
for comment on the Yilmaz's statement.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece signed a joint defense pact in 1993,
under which Greece pledges to join Cyprus in resisting any
possible military attack.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus announced in January this year its plan to buy S-300
missiles from Russia and their delivery will be made by mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided since
1974 when Turkish troops landed and took over 37 percent of
the island in the wake of a failed Greek Cypriot coup
seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
