<HEADLINE> Charter Changes After 1998 Elections: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos said today that changes in the country's constitution will
take place only after the 1998 elections by the way of a
constitutional convention.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Ramos said delegates to the
convention must be elected simultaneously during the May 11, 1998,
national elections.
</P>
<P>
Ramos made the final decision to shelve plans for charter
changes after receiving the results of wide-ranging consultation
recently conducted by some of his cabinet members across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The results of the consultation, he said, was that perhaps a
most expeditious way to change the charter after 1998 is a
constitutional convention.
</P>
<P>
"The main issues that have to be discussed were not so much the
constitutional issues but the socio-economic condition of our
country because people (consulted) are involved and interested in
many things starting with their daily lives," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos announced unexpectedly on Saturday that he will not run
for re-election and that the national and local elections would be
held in 1998 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"I say to you that, as the outgoing president, I will see to it
that there will be an orderly transfer of the presidency and all
its powers to my elected successor -- whoever he or she is," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' turnaround on the charter change, which was called for
by his supporters in an effort to extend his term, turned a
massive protest rally attended by hundreds of thousands of people
today into a peaceful thanks-giving gathering in which he was
praised for his new stance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
