<HEADLINE> Nigeria Defends Position on S. Leone Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's leadership position
in west Africa, as well as African tradition of being "our
brothers keeper", was the main factor that led to its
intervention in the Sierra Leonean crisis, President General Sani
Abacha said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"It is the only way we will effectively meet the domestic and
external demands as a leader in the sub-continent," Abacha told
the 44 regular course of the Nigeria Defense Academy in Kaduna,
northern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, he said, Nigeria has for the past few years
been undertaking significant re-organization of the armed forces
in order to create a cost effective, compact and mobile armed
forces that will be recognized for high professionalism and
combat readiness at all times.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian troops have played a key role in the west African
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG which successfully brought
peace back to Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The force is now also involved in the resolution of the crisis
in Sierra Leone, where coupists overthrew the legitimate
government in May this year.
</P>
<P>
"There is no disputing the fact that the successful
performance of our troops in ECOMOG owed a great deal to their
glorious exploits and exemplary performance," Abacha noted.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that his administration places a high premium
not only on defense, sovereignty and territorial integrity of the
country, but also on national security.
</P>
<P>
National security is a prerequisite for the enthronement of
democracy in Nigeria, he said, adding that the government has put
in place measures to lay a solid foundation for a viable and
sustainable democratic rule next year.
</P>
<P>
According to the military government's transition plan, the
current administration will be handed over to an elected
government on October 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
On the diplomatic front, Abacha said "While we have maintained
and will continue to maintain an open-door policy in relations
with our traditional allies, it has become imperative for us to
explore and open up new frontiers of positive and interactive
diplomacy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
