<HEADLINE> Indian PM to Visit Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral will visit Uganda on October 4 to 5, at the
invitation of Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni in a bid to lure
foreign investment, local daily The Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
Uganda will be the second African country after Tanzania to be
visited by the Indian prime minister. After Uganda, Gujiral will
proceed to South Africa at the invitation of President Nelson
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Gujral will be accompanied by a delegation of businessmen and
industrialists who will visit local factories.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and India have a long trade and social relationship. In
1972, however, the former Ugandan President Idi Amin expelled
more than 80,000 Asians, mostly Indians who controlled the core
investments in the country and gave their property to Africans.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, this policy of putting the economy in the hands
of Africans bungled and Uganda's once envied economy in the
region went down the drain, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
When Museveni came into power in 1986, he launched a campaign
to lure back the expelled and dispossessed Asians to Uganda. Many
of them have regained their property and the decaying factories
have been revived.
</P>
<P>
Now there are a number of heavy and light industrial factories
all over the country which are built by the new surge of Indian
investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Refuses to Identify Egypt's Decision on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Less than two months before the
controversial Fourth Middle East and North Africa Economic (MENA)
Conference is convened, President Hosni Mubarak still refused to
say whether Egypt will attend it or not.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab countries such as Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates, Lebanon and Syria have decided to boycott the conference
scheduled for November in the Qatari capital of Doha, to which
Israel is expected to be invited.
</P>
<P>
"I spoke about this matter before and I would only be repeating
myself if I talked about it now," Mubarak told reporters today
after inaugurating the second stage of the Cairo underground metro
second line.
</P>
<P>
The peace process is backtracking, he said, adding that Egypt is
waiting to see what will happen in Ras al-Amud, an Arab
neighborhood in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's statement comes after Israeli-Palestinian relations
deteriorated further last Sunday when Israeli settlers moved into
two houses in Ras al-Amud.
</P>
<P>
He said Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat
has described what is happening there and the Israeli announcement
of a settlement for this problem as a maneuver.
</P>
<P>
"We will just wait and see whether it is really a maneuver or
not," he added.
</P>
<P>
Although the Israelis withdrew under a compromise with Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, the buildings remain under Israeli
control, further infuriating the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In his earlier statements, Mubarak said Egypt's participation
in the regional economic forum involving Israel hinges on progress
in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, in a more clear-cut language perhaps for the first
time, a senior Egyptian official Saturday expressed opposition to
the convocation of the MENA conference.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt does not wish the conference would be held in a sisterly
Arab country like Qatar and then fail," Osama el-Baz, presidential
advisor for political affairs, told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
It will be "detrimental rather than beneficial" to convene the
conference under current circumstances, he said, adding that the
optimism over peace that prevailed the third MENA conference held
in Cairo last November is now regrettably missing in the region.
</P>
<P>
As a direct spinoff of the Mideast peace process, the annual
MENA conference had been held in Casablanca, Morocco; Amman,
Jordan; and Cairo, Egypt since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Most Arab countries have threatened to boycott it due to
Israel's participation. Qatar had been insisting on going ahead as
planned, refusing to link the summit with the peace process. But
emerging from a meeting held to forge a unified Arab stance
towards the MENA conference Saturday, Qatari Foreign Minister
Sheikh Hamad Ben Jassem Ben Jaber Al-Thani said his country also
believed that the conference would not secure the aspired success
unless a "tangible progress was made to the peace process and
Israel changes its current policy".
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of Syria, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Arab League
Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid also attended the meeting on
the sidelines of the 108th session of the Arab League foregin
ministers council, which began on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
