<HEADLINE> Tide Festival In East China Attracts Many Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 21 (Xinhua) -- About 800,000 Chinese and
overseas tourists attended the five-day 1997 International
Qiantang River Tide Festival that closed in Haining, Zhejiang
Province, today.
</P>
<P>
The annual event on the Qiantang River, where the tides are
regarded as one of 22 wonders of China, during the mid-Autumn
Festival is a tradition that goes back 800 years. The festival is
also a major tourism program in Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
Residents say that on September 19, or August 18 on the lunar
calendar, tides on the river were 2.5 meters high, the highest
level since 1971.
</P>
<P>
The event was sponsored by the Zhejiang Tourism Administration
and Jiaxing City Government, which added a fashion fair for furs,
song and dance performances, a painting exhibition and a lantern
show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
