<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Bombs Freetown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Planes of the west African
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG air shelled the Sierra Leonean
capital Freetown again on Saturday, dropping at least five bombs
on the harbor area.
</P>
<P>
No casualty was reported after the bombardment, the Sunday
Tribune said today.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is mandated by west African leaders to impose an
economic embargo on Sierra Leone to press the ruling junta to
restore the civilian government it ousted in a coup in May this
year.
</P>
<P>
The force has launched several air raids to stop vessels
accused of unloading arms and ammunition at the port since the
embargo was enforced after west African leaders made the decision
at a summit last month.
</P>
<P>
The embargo is reported to have led to split in Sierra Leone's
ruling armed forces revolutionary council, whose 30 out of 40
members moved for the reinstatement of ousted President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Captain S. A. Musa, chief secretary of the Sierra Leonean
military government who moved the motion, reportedly cautioned at
a council meeting over the weekend that "we cannot run a country
when both local and international community are against us".
</P>
<P>
In addition to the emerging spread of diseases and food
shortage, the embargo has led to worsening economy in the
troubled country.
</P>
<P>
Latest report quoted Finance Ministry official as saying that
Sierra Leone continued to register a negative economic growth
since the coup in May, with a deficit of over 8.5 million U.S.
Dollars as of September 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
At peace time, the government generated 70 percent of its
revenue from customs. But customs operation has been grounded as
a result of non arrival of vessels after the coup, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
The closure of banks and other businesses worsened the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
