planned to publish a news weekly in New York city next month, a
local newspaper reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The Brooklyn-based journal will cover regional affairs and
serve "undeserved" community of different colors in the city.
</P>
<P>
The so called minority population in New York is the majority
population and is ignored, said Milton Allimadi, publisher of the
weekly.
</P>
<P>
There were not enough publications serving them and there is a
big market, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The weekly will provide African Americans, Western Indians,
recent immigrants from Africa, Latin Americans and Asian
Americans with general news, investigative reports, business
profiles and features, The Monitor said in its report.
</P>
<P>
The journal with 28-32 pages will be sold at 50 cents in
newsstands in the metropolitan and run in 20,000 copies in its
initial stage of publication.
</P>
<P>
Allimadi, the editor, and Ben Otunu, business manager of the
tabloid, are Ugandans. 
