<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriots Pledged Goodwill to Enter Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said today that the Greek Cypriot side will enter a
dialog on security issues with the Turkish Cypriot side with good
will.
</P>
<P>
Clerides was referring to an agreed meeting between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriots, announced last Monday by U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright during a stop over here on her way back
to Washington after her Middle East tour.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to reporters, President Clerides expressed hope
the Turkish Cypriot side will also show good will.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot president called security as "one of the
fundamental issues" of the Cyprus problem and said he expects an
initiative for an overall settlement after the presidential
elections in Cyprus in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that his ultimate aim is "the reunification of
the island, the removal of Turkish troops occupying 37 percent of
its territory since they invaded in 1974, the safeguarding of
human rights and the peaceful coexistence of all communities".
</P>
<P>
Clerides expressed optimism that a peaceful settlement of the
Cyprus problem will be reached, with the help of Greece and a
joint defense pact between the two countries signed in 1993, as
well as the efforts of overseas Hellenes and foreign countries and
personalities.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-led direct peace talks between Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, held in the U.S. and
Switzerland in July and August, ended in failure as Denktash
refused to further negotiate a settlement unless the European
Union freezes its scheduled accession talks with Cyprus early 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when
Turkish troops landed on the island and took over the northern
third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the island as a bi-communal, bi-zonal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
