<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Official Says Stock Market Restriction Necessary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Imposing some restrictions
on foreign capital flowing into Thailand's stock market is
necessary at the present stage, a Thai official said here today.
</P>
<P>
While proper use of foreign capital is helpful to domestic
economic development, it is also important to retain some control
measures "if you are facing a financial crisis", said Prasarn
Trairatvorakul, deputy secretary general of the Thai Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a seminar on Asian stock markets, which
was part of a series of related events prior to the annual
meetings of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund to
be held on September 23-25.
</P>
<P>
Describing liberalization of capital flows on stock markets as
a "long-term trend", Prasarn said restrictions will eventually be
removed so as to ensure higher capital efficiency.
</P>
<P>
But many Asian stock markets including the Thai market are
still vulnerable to unexpected changes, and they have to
experience a transition period, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some sectors in Asian countries are fragile and they need
"certain level of protection" in order to keep "social harmony",
he said.
</P>
<P>
"In such a transition period, some restrictions have to be
retained," he said, adding that the problem is how to manage the
transition.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government now imposes a maximum 49 percent on foreign
shareholding. In some sectors such as banking and finance, the
limit is 25 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
