<HEADLINE> Indian Government, Suzuki Fail to Settle Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government and
Japan's Suzuki Motor Corporation on Saturday failed to resolve
their dispute over the appointment of a new managing director for
their car-making joint venture, Maruti Udyog Limited, the local
press said today.
</P>
<P>
After three-and-half hours of talks on the suggestion of the
Delhi High Court, both sides sticked to their hardline position.
</P>
<P>
The dispute flared up on August 27 when the board of Maruti
Udyog Limited decided to appoint RSSLN Bhaskarudu, an Indian
government nominee, as new managing director of the 50:50
Indian-Japanese joint venture.
</P>
<P>
Strongly opposing the appointment of Bhaskarudu, Suzuki
contended that as per its agreement with the Indian government,
the appointment of managing director could be made only on
obtaining concurrence from the Japanese side.
</P>
<P>
Suzuki filed a petition in the Delhi High Court in a bid to
stay the appointment of Bhaskarudu as managing director of the
joint venture.
</P>
<P>
At a hearing on Friday, the court reserved its order on the
Suzuki plea till Monday this week and suggested that the parties
concerned resolve their dispute through talks.
</P>
<P>
During the talks on Saturday, the Indian Industry Ministry
representatives made it clear that there was no question of
reconsideration of Bhaskarudu's appointment while the Japanese
side persisted with its demand for appointing a
mutually-acceptable government nominee.
</P>
<P>
Failing to settle their dispute, both sides said they would
report to the Delhi High Court which will resume hearing of the
case tomorrow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
