<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Urges Governments to Guard against Banking Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Senior Vice-President and
Chief Economist of the World Bank Joseph Stiglitz today warned
governments against risks from underregulating the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
"Although the dangers of overregulation are substantial, we
also must avoid the other extreme of underregulating banks," he
said in a key-note speech to a World Bank seminar on Building
Better Banking here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that in particular, governments must pay more attention
to designing better incentives and legal systems including
auditing standards that encourage bank owners, bank managers, and
their clients to take an active part in self-monitoring and
self-regulating.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries in particular are prone to economy-wide
shocks because their production is less diverse, their policy more
volatile, and their terms of trade subject to greater shocks, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, developing countries have fewer
risk-absorbing institutions and less risk absorption capacity
within risk management institutions.
</P>
<P>
"In combination with a fragile financial system, this can send
these economies into a vicious circle in which the initial shock
triggers banking problems which in turn exacerbate the shock," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"For developing countries it may be necessary to have higher
capital requirements," he said, adding that different situations
should be taken into account in all areas of policy-making.
</P>
<P>
He said the stability of the banking system is an important
goal, but it is not the only objective.
</P>
<P>
The nature of the regulatory structure needs to be tuned to
capacities of countries as well as the nature of the risks being
faced, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that governments must play an essential role in the
regulation of the financial system.
</P>
<P>
Understanding and promoting the necessary reforms will be one
of the World Bank's most vital jobs over the next decade, Stiglitz
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Lending to Low Income Countries Fruitful: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Developments in the 36
low-income countries supported by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) through the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF)
in the last one or two years are very encouraging, according to an
IMF report here today.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "IMF Lending to Low-Income Countries -- 10
Years Experience," said that the countries undertaking programs of
adjustment and reform have brought their economies a long way from
the doldrums of the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Real per-capita output growth among non-transition ESAF users
has, on average, caught up with that in other developing
countries, it said.
</P>
<P>
The social indicators in most of these countries have improved,
budget deficits have been trimmed and instances of very high
inflation almost eliminated.
</P>
<P>
The improving trend has also helped narrow the gap between
growth in ESAF users and other developing countries, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
For instance, in the early 1980s, annual average per-capita
growth in non-ESAF developing countries exceeded that in
non-transition ESAF countries by around 2.2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
But this differential had been more than halved to 0.9 points
by 1995, it said.
</P>
<P>
The 36 low-income nations, or ESAF users include 30
non-transition countries -- 22 in Africa, four in Asia, four in
South America -- and six transition economies.
</P>
<P>
The non-transition countries in the CFA Franc zone have
succeeded in maintaining inflation consistently in the low single
digit range since the mid-1980s, it said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the report also admitted that on average, only
half of the targeted reduction in primary budget deficits was
achieved.
</P>
<P>
The report suggested that the ESAF countries adopt an
adjustment strategy to raise saving rates, secure macro-economic
stability, liberalize and open economies to foreign trade, reduce
government intervention and promote well-functioning markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank's IFC Eager to Work with New Clients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC), a member of the World Bank Group, is eager to
reach new countries, develop new products and work with new
clients, a senior IFC official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, IFC Executive Vice-President
Jannik Lindbaek said that the 1997 fiscal year was a year of
innovation and change for the corporation with its activities in
more countries and development of more products than ever before.
</P>
<P>
"We are crossing new frontiers, diversifying our product mix,
and shifting our focus away from the countries where we are less
relevant to those where we are more needed," Lindbaek said.
</P>
<P>
The IFC's strategy is to "reach new countries, develop new
products, and work with new clients," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IFC, he said, was ready to center its future efforts on the
spheres of infrastructure, environment, technical assistance and
advisory services, privatization, extending IFC's reach, capital
markets, increased coverage of stock markets and support for micro
finance.
</P>
<P>
To finance its lending program, the IFC borrowed a total of
approximately four billion U.S. dollars in the 1997 fiscal year,
almost all of which was accessed through the international capital
market, and approved investments in most major infrastructure
subsectors including transport service, utilities, power, and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is the private sector arm of the World Bank Group and
the largest multilateral source of equity and loan financing for
private sector projects in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment just over 41 years ago, the IFC's
syndication program has placed participation of nearly 14 billion
U.S. dollars with some 380 financial institutions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
