<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Egyptians Hanged for Killing Kuwaiti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Two Egyptians were hanged
this morning in Kuwaiti Central Prison after being found guilty of
murdering a Kuwaiti citizen in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Kuwaiti Interior Ministry said the two
Egyptians Hamdi Abdel Azim and Hassan Abdel Haditwo were found
guilty of killing Bader Al-Walaan, a Kuwaiti citizen, in 1996 and
disposing of his body in a deserted mosque.
</P>
<P>
In Kuwait, death punishment must obtain ratification from the
Amir of the country.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the death sentence against the two men was
ratified by the Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah after the two
were sentenced to death by the Criminal Court and the Court of
Cassation, the highest judicial authority in the country.
</P>
<P>
Today's executions bring to eight the number of capital
punishment sentences carried out in Kuwait since the country's
liberation from the Iraqi occupation in February 1991.
</P>
<P>
The first execution of an Iraqi, who was found guilty of
killing a Kuwaiti border guard while resisting arrest, was
carried out in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
The previous execution was carried out in September 1996 when a
Kuwaiti interior ministry officer Bader Abdel Karim Sultan
Al-Bashir was executed after being convicted of killing a Syrian
woman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
