<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Likud Calls for Forming National Unity Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Justice Minister
Tzahi Hanegbi has publicly voiced his support to forming a
national unity government to solve the current crisis facing the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio Saturday night, Hanegebi said
such a unity government was "a necessity." He said that Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and opposition Labor Party leader Ehud
Barak have ways to discuss this issue even before an official
invitation for such a move is actually issued.
</P>
<P>
Hanegbi, who forms Netanyahu's hard-core support within the
Cabinet together with Health Minister Yehoshua Matza and Science
Minister Michael Eitan, added that he believed Netanyahu and
Barak could reach agreement on major issues in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The idea of a broad government was first explored jointly by
National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and Labor's former
Prime Minister Shimon Peres following Netanyahu's election
victory last year.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was dismissed at that time across the political
spectrum as a last-ditch attempt by both to salvage their personal
political fortunes. However, it re-surfaced in the wake of the
recent wave of terror attacks in Jerusalem that worsened the peace
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on television following the September 4 suicide
bombings, lawmaker Yehuda Harel of the coalition party The Third
Way said a unity government was "inevitable," adding that the only
question was whether it would be formed before or after "the next
disaster."
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that a Labor-Likud coalition now appears
more possible than it seemed immediately after Netanyahu's rise to
power last June, considering that Netanyahu has since dealt openly
with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and its president,
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Netanyahu's talk this year of an "Allon-Plus" deal
on a permanent settlement between Israel and the PNA signaled a
break from traditional Likud dogma on territorial compromise, and
brought him at least theoretically closer to Barak's views.
</P>
<P>
Within Labor, Barak's major ally Uzi Baram last week softened
his previously uncompromising opposition to a national unity
government, saying there may be circumstances under which he would
espouse the idea.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process has been mired in crisis since
Israel began building the Har Homa settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem in March. The recent terrorist attacks against Israel
and the dispute over Ras Al-Amud Jewish settlement project
deepened the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Peres, however, publicly denied the possibility of forming a
unity government in a speech Saturday night to the Foreign Press
Association in Jerusalem. He blasted Netanyahu for trying to make
peace without any price, warning that a war would be a more
expensive price to pay for Israel.
</P>
<P>
Till now, Barak has also ruled out joining a unity government.
The former Army Chief of Staff has said that his only aim was to
topple and replace the Likud government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Philippine President: No Way for Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Former Philippine President
Corazon Aquino today called for every effort to stop Charter
change moves seeking to extend the term of President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Addressing to participants of a massive protest rally against
Charter changes in Luneta Park, Manila, she said she would tell
the people who wants to stay in power by martial law or Charter
changes "no way and never again".
</P>
<P>
The former president praised Ramos for his efforts in
establishing political stability, achieving economic prosperity
and restoring the confidence of the country throughout the world.
But meanwhile, she urged him to step down as his term ends next
year.
</P>
<P>
"Trust the good people of the our country to continue your good
work. I trusted you when my term was over, trust in the
Filipinos," she said.
</P>
<P>
Catholic Church leader Cardinal Jaime Sin said the Charter
change moves, causing divisiveness in the country, are "immoral"
and will benefit only some individuals. He urged Ramos to turn
over his power peacefully in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The rally, attended by Cardinal Sin, Vice President Joseph
Estrada, congressmen, local government leaders and some one
million people, was held peacefully despite warnings that it would
be bombed by saboteurs and the efforts the government made to
prepare for the worst.
</P>
<P>
Protest rallies against Charter changes were also held
peacefully in other parts of the country on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the rally, Ramos said on Saturday that he would step
down next year and "would not run for re-election," stunning many
people who believe he would seek a second term through Charter
changes.
</P>
<P>
"I am fully satisfied with having served as your president for
one six-year term as mandated in the constitution," Ramos said.
</P>
</TEXT>
