<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Buy Saudi Arabian Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is
expecting to sell arms to Saudi Arabia in exchange for oil from
the gulf state, local daily Sunday Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
Pretoria has offered to buy oil from Saudi Arabia as a
counter-trade arrangement in the seven billion Rand (148 million
U.S. Dollars) arms deal which is about to be finalized with
Riyadh, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Local observers believe that the move to import oil from Saudi
Arabia is an indication that the South African government wants
to reduce its reliance on Iran, which currently provides more
than two-thirds of this country's fuel imports.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia's Second Deputy Premier, Defense and Aviation
Minister Abdul-Aziz al Saud arrived in Cape Town on Wednesday for
a six-day state visit, during which he was expected to meet
President Nelson Mandela and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
He is also scheduled to meet South African Defense Minister
Joe Modise and Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs Penuell
Maduna.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Saudis were negotiating to buy G-6
mobile artillery pieces and anti-aircraft missiles from South
Africa in what will be the biggest deal in the history of the
defense history of this country.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is scheduled to visit Saudi Arabia in November, which
will be his third visit to the kingdom since his release from
jail in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
