<HEADLINE> Ramos Calls for National Unity Before Opposition Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today called for national unity about two hours before a
massive protest rally against Charter change moves starts in Metro
Manila.
</P>
<P>
In an arrival statement from a four-nation visit, Ramos said
the Philippines could become a more powerful economy by the 21st
century if the Filipinos do not allow their economic gains to be
eroded by politically-inspired divisiveness and factionalism.
</P>
<P>
"The past five years have shown that we can achieve the destiny
that Jose Rizal and our other great heroes, including Ninoy
Aquino, had envisioned for all of us, if we work together, and not
against each other; If we speak with reason, and not anger; If we
have faith in one another, and not mistrust," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos hoped today's scheduled rally would go on peacefully so
that the people can all go back to work and strive together harder
than ever for "a better future for the country and the people."
</P>
<P>
Analysts said charter change moves seeking to extend the term
of Ramos is causing divisiveness and political uncertainty in the
country, prompting church leaders to call for the protest rally.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, Ramos had kept everyone guessing
whether he would stay in power or step down when his term ends in
June next year. The Constitution allows him to serve only a
six-year single term.
</P>
<P>
Although he promised Friday that he would not run for a second
term and has urged the stopping of charter change moves, he failed
to stop anti-charter change people from taking to the streets
today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
