<HEADLINE> Zambia to Rehabilitate Two Main Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is
looking for 51 million U.S. Dollars to rehabilitate the
Livingstone and Ndola airports to internationally accepted
standards, Sunday Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
The two airports have been identified for rehabilitation
because of a growing potential and an anticipated tourism boom.
</P>
<P>
The runway in use at Livingstone Airport built in the early
1950s has a restricted load bearing capacity and the length for a
Boeing 737.
</P>
<P>
The airport in the south of Zambia has no hangars nor terminal
buildings and taxiway while Ndola airport in the north needs
expansion for the provision of more cargo warehouses, offices and
hangars.
</P>
<P>
Livingstone alone needs 36 million dollars and Ndola needs 15
million dollars for their rehabilitation, according to Jimmy
Zulu, assistant secretary for air in the Ministry of
Communication and Transport.
</P>
<P>
"The improvements are necessary for us to compete favorably
with our Zimbabwean counterparts to support the tourism industry
in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ndola needs expansion as indications are showing an increase
in traffic because of the on-going privatization of Zambia
Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), Zulu said.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation work will take 36 months to compete
for Livingstone and 24 months for Ndola airport when funds are
available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Start Hunting Illegal Migrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is to start a
nationwide campaign to hunt foreign nationals illegally living in
the country ahead of the December Gulf Cooperation Council summit.
</P>
<P>
Informed official sources said today that a meeting was held by
senior Interior Ministry officials over the weekend to discuss
security preparations for the summit and instruct security forces
to launch a search campaign against illegal expatriates.
</P>
<P>
They said security officers were asked to comb various areas
for suspected infiltrators and illegals until the GCC summit is
held.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sources said, the Ministry of Interior has
instructed directors of the immigration departments of Kuwait's
five governorates to adopt strict measures in granting visas to
nationals of Arab countries which sided with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Large number of foreign nationals, mainly from neighboring
countries, flocked into Kuwait to seek jobs. Constant search for
illegal Arab and Asian laborers have been conducted in the country
which hosts 1.25 million foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Interior Ministry arrested 416 infiltrators who
illegally entered the country during the first half of 1997,
official figures showed.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait courts traditionally jail illegal migrants for six
months before they are deported at their own expense out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
This campaign coincided with increased efforts to crack down on
illegal migrants in other Gulf Arab countries such as Saudi Arabia
and the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The UAE will start searching for illegal migrants after a
five-month amnesty allowing them to leave ends late this month.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia started raids on illegal migrants this month in
order to drive out 100,000 illegal aliens from the kingdom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
