<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Frontier of Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Asian businessmen find that
Africa, increasingly referred to as the new frontier of global
investment, has brought them with ample opportunities along with
some difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Conrad Strauss, moderator of a World Bank seminar on
Opportunities for Asian Investors in Africa, said today that
Africa may be small in global perspective, but it is neither small
in geographic and demographic term, nor small in economic
potential.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank estimates that private investment, which rose
from less than one billion US dollars in the early 1990s to 11.7
billion US dollars in 1996, now accounts for about 45 percent of
the total capital flow into Africa.
</P>
<P>
Cha Chi Ming, a Hong Kong textile industrialist, shared his
30-year experience of business expansion in Africa with
participants at the seminar, held prior to the annual meetings of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) scheduled
for September 23-25 in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"I represent people who learned their trade in Asia and
deployed their lessons in Africa," said Cha, whose family company
built first textile plant in Nigeria in 1964, and ever since, has
expanded factories to Ghana and Togo and been profitable in each
of the 33 years.
</P>
<P>
"It is best to assist by investing in their local industries,
thereby creating a thriving economy rather than providing aid from
time to time," he said.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that there is a need to nourish and protect
growing economies since most African countries do not have a big
enough local market.
</P>
<P>
"These fences will not be a permanent feature and will come
down when the local economies and industries are strong enough to
stand on their own," said the businessman, who won the Grand
Bauhinia Medal, the highest award in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
Joseph Gondobintoro, chairman of a Singapore-based company
which has recently been active in Africa, summed up his experience
by saying that there are ample opportunities in African countries,
yet potential investors should take time to make in-depth studies
of viable markets.
</P>
<P>
Problems do arise, he said, from differences in cultures and
lifestyles between Africa and Asia, such as local people's
suspicion of foreigners and rampant lower-level bureaucratic
interference.
</P>
<P>
Gondobintoro mentioned two factors critical to the success of
investment -- seeking a reliable local partner and understanding
local government operation.
</P>
<P>
Other speakers at the discussion agreed that abundant natural
resources, coupled with the recent deregulation and privatization
process, make Africa an attractive market to investors.
</P>
<P>
But much has to be done to achieve a broad-based economic
growth. Governments need to build adequate infrastructure, develop
financial sectors, and maintain social and political stability,
they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
