<HEADLINE> Croatia Condemns Mostar Car Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Croatian Foreign Minister Mate
Granic today strongly condemned Thursday's car bombing in Mostar,
describing it as a form of the most ruthless terrorist activity
launched against the consolidation and peace process of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The terrorists are trying to hamper the implementation of the
agreements signed last month in Split, a coastal city of Croatia,
between Croat President Franjo Tudjman and President of the
Bosnian Presidency Alija Izetbegovic, said Granic.
</P>
<P>
A powerful explosion, which went off near the police station in
the Croat-controlled western Mostar, injured 50 people.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred shortly after the signing of the
agreements which adopted complaints of the Bosnian Croat political
leadership and the local elections in Bosnia, particularly in
Mostar.
</P>
<P>
Croat Defense Minister Gojko Susak, Co-president of the Bosnian
Council of Ministers Neven Tomic and Bosnian Foreign Minister
Jadranko Prlic today also issued a statement, calling the
terrorist attack "another attempt aimed at destablizing the peace
process in Bosnia-Herzegovina." 
</P>
