<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call for Diversification in Banking Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A number of international
banking experts today urged banks to diversify their risks in
financial business in order to avoid possible shocks.
</P>
<P>
Experts attending a seminar on "Building Better Banking" here
today agreed that the issue of banking system fragility has moved
to the top of the international agenda and diversification will
play an important role in preventing systematic problems in the
banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, attended by more than 200 senior officials,
bankers and researchers, was part of a series of seminars prior to
the annual meetings of the World Bank and International Monetary
Fund (IMF) scheduled for September 23-25 in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the current currency upheavals in Southeast Asia,
Gerard Caprio, a World Bank economist, and Berry Wilson, senior
economist at the U.S. Federal Communications Commission, pointed
out that lack of diversification is part of the causes leading to
the Thai Baht crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Thai financial sector may consequently be vulnerable to
further economic shocks following the Baht devaluation, the two
experts said.
</P>
<P>
Although insufficient diversification is not the only reason
for bank failure, it will be safer for banks to lend in a
diversified pattern, instead of in a concentrated way, they said.
</P>
<P>
"If authorities focus on what they can do to ensure that
bankers are motivated to diversify their risks, and indeed that
they devote significant attention to planning for various shocks
to their balance sheets, then the next 15 years should see far
fewer banking crises than have been experienced in the preceding
ones," the experts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
