<HEADLINE> SADC not Splitting: Zimbabwean Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Nathan Shamuyarira,
Zimbabwean Minister of Industry and Commerce Saturday brushed
aside rumours of a split in the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) as being unfounded.
</P>
<P>
He told the Sunday Mail that Zimbabwe would be strengthening
its position in the region, ready to take advantage of present
initiatives to achieve greater regional economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Following the SADC meeting in Blantyre, Malawi where member
countries agreed to ratify the trade protocol, Zimbabwe had had
the protocol approved by cabinet and it will now be taken to the
parliament next week for ratification. Ratification of the
protocol by all member states would be a sign that all nations
are committed to stronger and freer trade among themselves.
</P>
<P>
"SADC is getting strong. This is shown by the fact that we
had two members joining at the Blantyre meeting -- the Democratic
Republic of Congo and the Seychelles-- while a third, Madagascar,
has applied and will be considered at the next summit", said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Reports of a split in SADC emerged after the Blantyre summit
where Zimbabwe and South Africa differed on the role of a SADC
organ on defense and politics. South Africa was reported to be
pushing for the organ to be swallowed up by SADC while Zimbabwe
preferred that it continued to hold its own meetings.
</P>
<P>
"The general feeling is that it should be kept separate and
parallel with SADC because there are a number of issues
pertaining to defense and politics that can't be handled by an
economic body like SADC," said Shamuyarira. 
</P>
</TEXT>
