<HEADLINE> South Asia's Continued Growth Calls for Further Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Speakers at seminars prior
to the annual meetings of the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund here, today took pride in South Asia's relatively
high growth rate in recent years, but urged further reforms and
infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
During the past decade, South Asia has been the second fastest
growing region in the world after East Asia, with an average
annual growth of over five percent thanks to sweeping economic
reforms across the region, they noted.
</P>
<P>
India, the giant in the region, has seen a seven percent growth
for the third year in a row.
</P>
<P>
At today's session entitled "South Asia: The Next Miracle?",
speakers reviewed the crucial factors that lie behind the
remarkable rates of growth in East Asia to see what South Asia can
learn from its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
John Williamson, chief economist at the World Bank, summarized
seven key factors as contributing to East Asia's success,
including macro-economic stability, high domestic savings,
export-led growth, universal education and high foreign investment
inflows.
</P>
<P>
His views were shared by Surjit Bhalla, president of India's
Oxus Research and Investment, and Lal Jayawardena, advisor to the
president and deputy chairman of Sri Lanka's National Development
Council.
</P>
<P>
Jayawardena also laid emphasis on two priorities high on the
agenda of South Asian countries -- labor market reform and
agriculture reform -- to ensure continued growth.
</P>
<P>
At a session Saturday, the first day of four days of seminars
organized by the World Bank and the IMF, Deputy President Kenji
Yoshizawa of the Bank of Tokyo urged India to accelerate
infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Japanese investment in India since 1991 has been a mere 1.5
billion US dollars, in sharp contrast with the 23 billion US
dollars pouring into China, Yoshizawa noted. The Japanese's main
concern lies in India's poor physical infrastructure, he said.
</P>
<P>
Richard Fisher, chairman of the executive committee at the
international investment bank Morgan Stanley, commented that it is
necessary for India to further improve its financial market
infrastructure so as to attract foreign investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
