<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil political
parties have reaffirmed their support to the government's peace
process and urged President Chandrika Kumaratunga to ignore the
extremists' attempts to disrupt the peace initiatives, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Tamil United Liberation Front (TULF)
President Murugesu Sivasithamparam as saying that whenever there
was a healthy approach to the ethnic issue, the extremist forces
were all out to destroy it.
</P>
<P>
"Past events remain a good lesson for the present generation of
politicians to take meaningful steps in solving the ethnic crisis.
We earnestly urge the president to stand by her peace initiatives
to end the ethnic conflict," the party leader said.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on an interim report of the Sinhala
Commission published on Wednesday, which rekindled a political
controversy across the nation by opposing the devolution proposals
of the government.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposals, more autonomy would be given to the
northern and eastern provinces, where the Tamil rebels have been
fighting a guerrilla war for a separate state since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Savumyamoorthy Thondaman, leader of the Ceylon Workers
Congress, said that the extremist forces spoilt the peace attempts
whenever they surfaced in the political arena. He urged the
president to go ahead with the government's peace moves and ignore
the extremists.
</P>
<P>
D. Sitharthan of the People's Liberation Organization of Tamil
Eelam said the current peace package is the only hope for the
Tamils.
</P>
<P>
He added that the report of the Sinhala Commission, a political
organization headed by former Supreme Court Judge S. W. Walpita,
will definitely harm the genuine peace efforts. He expressed the
hope that the president will overcome such obstacles.
</P>
<P>
Some other politicians also voiced their support to the
devolution proposals of the president and criticized the interim
report. 
