<HEADLINE> Iran Arrests an Editor-in-Chief on Spying Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The editor-in-chief of local
English language daily Iran News has been arrested on charges of
spying for Iran's arch enemy, the United States, the Kayhan Havaia
weekly reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly, believed to have good connection with Iranian
intelligence, said that Morteza Firoozi had been arrested by
Iranian security officers a few weeks ago - no exact date was
given.
</P>
<P>
The chief of the editing board of the three-year-old daily,
widely-believed a "liberal" newspaper, had also been advisor to a
top government official, said the report, without specifying.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no official information about the arrest.
</P>
<P>
S. Bozorgmehr, one of the executive editors of daily, told
Xinhua on telephone that it was the first time for him to hear of
the news.
</P>
<P>
He was informed that Firoozi had gone to Britain for study,
Bozorgmehr added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kayhan Havaia noted that Iran News had failed to
observe obvious national interests. One of the daily's executive
editors also represents America's Cable News Networks (CNN) in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Faraj Sarkouhi, a liberal editor of the Persian
Weekly Adineh, was sentenced to one year in prison.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Revolution Court said here today that Sarkouhi was
found guilty of having secret contacts with some European
nationals and of involvement in anti-Iran propaganda campaigns.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested along with his brother and two smugglers while
attempting to flee the country from Bushehr, a port city in
southern Iran, in February. 
</P>
