<HEADLINE> U.S. Supports Increased Southeast Asia's Voice in IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
supported a distribution of the quota shares of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) that will increase the voice and vote in the
IMF of a number of Southeast Asian countries, U.S. Secretary of
Treasury Robert Rubin said here today.
</P>
<P>
"This will reflect better these countries' importance in the
world economy and their capacity to undertake additional
responsibilities, as evidenced by their provision of bilateral
assistance during the recent (currency) crisis (in Southeast
Asia)," Rubin told a meeting of the IMF Interim Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said a quota increase will provide a welcome opportunity to
align member's quota shares in the IMF more closely with their
roles in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF Executive Board Saturday agreed to a 45 percent
increase in members' quotas worth a total of 88.4 billion U.S.
dollars. The Board also reached agreement on a special, one-time
allocation of 21.4 billion special drawing rights (SDR) that would
raise total SDR allocations to 42.9 billion SDRs.
</P>
<P>
"We also welcome the agreement on an amendment of the Articles
of Agreement to provide a special one-time allocation of SDRs
which will enable all members, and especially new IMF members, to
participate fully in the SDR arrangement," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that an adequately funded IMF must also stand ready
to play a larger role in responding to financial crises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
