<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paris Club Calls for Promoting Financial Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The finance ministers and
central bank governors of the Paris Club today stressed the need
of working out a concerted strategy to promote financial stability
in emerging market economies.
</P>
<P>
The participants "welcomed the broad endorsement given to the
concerted strategy to promote financial stability in emerging
market economies that have been developed in collaboration with
representatives of these economies," said a communique issued at
the end of a meeting of the G-10, also known as the Paris Club
composed of creditor nations.
</P>
<P>
They also paid attention to the stability of the international
monetary system and focused on such questions as crisis prevention
and crisis management, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
Given the financial market turmoil in Southeast Asia, which has
many of its roots in weak financial systems, the participants
stressed the importance of concrete and comprehensive
implementation of the concerted strategy, which focuses on actions
in three main areas:
</P>
<P>
-- Creating a macroeconomic and institutional setting favorable
to sound credit cultures and the efficient and continued operation
of markets;
</P>
<P>
-- Promoting effective stakeholder oversight and good
governance of financial institutions;
</P>
<P>
-- And Instituting sound regulatory and supervisory
arrangements that support and complement market discipline.
</P>
<P>
The participants, in this context, stressed the need for the
Paris Club to continue its efforts to promote implementation of
the concerted strategy in cooperation with representatives of
emerging market economies, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
They also welcomed the greater focus of the IMF's surveillance
on the financial sector and the emphasis given to strengthening
financial systems of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, British Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon
Brown was elected chairman of the Club for the coming year.
</P>
</TEXT>
