<HEADLINE> Beijing-Paris Motor rallists Reach Kathmandu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 21 (Xinhua) -- After a hard first
4700-kilometer journey, 84 of the 99 vintage cars taking part in
the second Beijing to Paris classic car rally reached this capital
city of Nepal on Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
These cars and their drivers will have a three-day break in
Kathmandu, doing necessary maintenance and patchup work.
</P>
<P>
Since the Beijing to Paris Motor Challenge took a
trans-Himalaya route to Nepal for the first time, these motorists
had to drive through the 17,000-foot-high Tanggu Pass, the highest
road in the world.
</P>
<P>
About 200 motorists from 22 countries are participating in the
16,000-kilometer-long rally, which started from Beijing on
September 5.
</P>
<P>
They will drive through 11 countries including India, Pakistan,
Iran, Turkey, Greece, Italy, Switzerland and Germany, and arrive
in Paris on October 18.
</P>
<P>
As the Visit Nepal Year '98 nears, Nepal pays much attention to
the rally.
</P>
<P>
This Himalayan kingdom plans to hold a vintage cars exhibition
and a reception for the participants on September 23.
</P>
<P>
Cars parked at Nepal's Birendra International Convention Center
range from a 1907 La France to Rolls Royce, Bentley, Mercedes,
Austin Martin, BMW, Porsche, Rover and Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
The rally is being organized by the Britain-based Classic Rally
Association.
</P>
<P>
During the first Beijing to Paris rally held in the summer of
1907, two of the five competing cars reached the destination
through the Silk Road. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
