<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD: Global FDI Reached $349 Billion in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The total amount of the global
foreign direct investment (FDI) reached 349 billion U.S. dollars
in 1996, a 10 percent rise over 1995, said a United Nations report
published today.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 208 billion dollars went into developed countries
and 129 billion dollars into developing countries, the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said in its
1997 World Investment Report.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD said that although the flows of FDI into the
developed countries continued to far exceed those into the
developing countries, the gap has been narrowing.
</P>
<P>
The record inflows of 129 billion dollars into the developing
countries were 34 percent up, compared to that of 1995, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, outflows from the developed countries were partly
up, at 295 billion dollars while those from the developing
countries accounted for 15 percent of the total FDI, or 51 billion
dollars, it added.
</P>
<P>
China is still the second largest FDI recipient in the world,
absorbing 42 billion dollars, which accounted for over 50 percent
of the total amount of the FDI inflows into Asia last year, the
report noted.
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD believed that China's large and growing market, ongoing
economic reforms, successful economic "soft landing", and measures
to promote inward investment have combined to yield that result.
</P>
<P>
The United States remained to be the largest FDI recipient by
attracting 85 billion dollars in 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Investment flows into the Latin American and Caribbean
countries reached 39 billion dollars, rising by 52 percent last
year. The increase is the highest of any developing region,
accounting for 30 percent of the total inflows to the developing
countries, it said.
</P>
<P>
About 105 billion dollars of the FDI inflows has gone into West
Europe while those into Central and East Europe has fallen to 12
billion dollars from 14 billion dollars in 1995, the report said.
</P>
<P>
FDI inflows remained very little for the 48 least developed
countries, only accounting for two percent of the total, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Inflation Shoots Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The hike in petroleum
products announced on September 1 took effect on India's annual
rate of inflation which rose sharply to 4.2 percent during the
week ending September 6, from 3.81 percent recorded in the
previous week, Press Trust of India said today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the official wholesale price index (WPI) moved up by
0.8 percent to 329.7 in the week under review from 327.1 points in
the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The index for fuel, power, light and lubricants' group rose by
a whopping 6 percent to 370.1 during the reference week from 349.2
points in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Higher prices of petroleum products such as high speed diesel
(up 30 percent) and liquefied petroleum gas (up 14 percent) caused
this steep hike.
</P>
<P>
Other commodities whose prices went up substantially during the
reference week included zinc (10 percent), fruits and vegetable (6
percent) and raw silk (4 percent).
</P>
<P>
The commodities showing a fall in prices included synthetic
filament yarn (down 5 percent), raw jute (down 4 percent) and
steel ingots (down 3 percent).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
