<HEADLINE> Nagano Organisers Under Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Ski
Federation (FIS) has threatened to take Japanese organisers to
international arbitration to get a longer men's downhill course at
next year's Nagano Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Amid environmental concerns, organisers have rejected the idea
of stretching the track into a national park where no building is
allowed.
</P>
<P>
But FIS president Marc Hodler insisted that the federation may
take the dispute to the Swiss-based Court of Arbitration for Sport.
</P>
<P>
The FIS hopes to raise the start point from 1,680 meters above
sea level to 1,800 meters to avoid putting on shortest men's
downhill in Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
The sports court, established by the International Olympic
Committee (IOC), has mediated in Olympic-related disputes,
including doping cases at the Atlanta Summer Games last year.
</P>
