<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Launch Hotline Service for AIDS Counseling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A 24-hour hotline service
for AIDS (acquired immune deficiency syndrome) counseling is being
launched in India from October 1, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
The hot-line service is part of the Indian government's new
drive to improve its AIDS control program which has suffered a
severe setback.
</P>
<P>
With the help of such a service, officials feel that they would
be able to help those who need help, but are hesitant to seek it.
The calls will be free of charge.
</P>
<P>
The hot-line service, which is to be allotted a three-digit
number, will give information on HIV (human immuno-deficiency
virus) and AIDS as well as help provide AIDS counseling to
individual cases.
</P>
<P>
A pre-recorded computerized service will guide the caller
through his queries. If it is unable to answer a question, the
caller will be given a query number and asked to get back after
some hours.
</P>
<P>
Later the caller will be required to punch in the query number
for seeking the answer to his call. If the caller wants a personal
counseling session then he would be given appointment over the
phone.
</P>
<P>
The AIDS control program sponsored by the government since 1987
has shown little success so far with the cases of HIV infection
growing several times.
</P>
<P>
There are already over 66,000 people in the country who are
infected with the virus. Of these, almost 5,000 are suffering from
full-blown AIDS.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
