<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camdessus Upbeat About Prospects of Thai Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Michel Camdessus, managing
director of the International Monetary Fund, today expressed
confidence in the prospects of the Thai economy despite the
current financial turmoil that has swept Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"There should be confidence that Thailand will gradually return
to the impressive growth trend observed in the past," Camdessus
said in a statement to the IMF Interim Committee here this
morning.
</P>
<P>
The Thai authorities have committed themselves to a strong
adjustment program and improved data reportings, he said, noting
that adjustments and reform are well under way.
</P>
<P>
The international community has given its substantial
endorsement and support to the measures taken by the Thai
authorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Provided the necessary policy adjustments are implemented
without delay, the currency turbulence should eventually wane,"
Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
For other countries with pegged exchange rate regimes to reduce
financial risks, Camdessus recommended that they introduce greater
flexibility in the management of their exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
Greater exchange rate flexibility can make it easier to deal
with external shocks that require domestic policy adjustments,
although it obviously cannot be a substitute for appropriate
macroeconomic policies, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It can also help deter speculative capital inflows and convey
a more realistic perception of risks to both domestic and foreign
investors," he said.
</P>
<P>
The managing director also emphasized the need to enhance the
transparency of government budgets and the quality and timeliness
of economic data to help reduce the risk of disruptive changes in
investor sentiment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
