<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Backs IMF's Strengthened Surveillance, Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Dai Xianglong, governor of
the People's Bank of China, said here today that China supports
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in its increased efforts to
strengthen its surveillance function.
</P>
<P>
Dai, who is here for the annual meetings of the World Bank and
the IMF on September 23-25, also stressed that the IMF should at
the same time strengthen dialogue with member countries in
conducting the surveillance.
</P>
<P>
"We support the Fund's increased efforts to strengthen its
surveillance function, particularly over those countries with
systemic repercussions," Dai said at the 49th meeting of the
Interim Committee of the IMF Board of Governors on the
International Monetary System.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile the Fund should take full account of member
countries' individual conditions and strengthen candid dialogue
with member countries in conducting the surveillance," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the progress in launching the data dissemination
standards and encourage further progress in this area," he
continued. "Not only can technical assistance help member
countries implement the Fund's policy advice and improve their
statistical work, but it can also help enhance the effectiveness
of Fund surveillance."
</P>
<P>
"The Fund should, therefore, continue to strengthen the
provision of technical assistance to the developing countries," he
added.
</P>
<P>
On the current economic situation worldwide, Dai said he was in
broad agreement with the Fund staff and the Board's assessments
and projections.
</P>
<P>
"A sustained strong growth momentum in the developing world, a
continued stable growth in the industrial countries as a whole,
and a positive growth for the first time in the transition
countries as a group have initially laid a good basis for future
sustained world economic development," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he cautioned people against neglecting the risks and
problems facing the global economy.
</P>
<P>
"The economic performance varies widely among major industrial
countries, reflecting the differences in their internal structural
weaknesses and reform intensity. Continental European countries
should strive to reduce fiscal deficits and unemployment so as to
attain a sustained growth," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
He also advised some industrial countries to maintain vigilance
against possible re-emergence of inflationary pressures. "Where
necessary, preemptive measures should be taken to preserve
long-term price stability," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
