<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Cabinet to Discuss Devolution Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Kumaratunga will present her government's proposed
constitutional reforms and devolution proposals at a special
cabinet meeting to be held at the end of this month, government
sources disclosed today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is scheduled to be held on September 29 and the
government will forward the parliament the final draft of the
constitutional reforms and the proposals for devolution in the
first week of October.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the People's Alliance (PA), the ruling party
which consists of six political parties, is to continue its
informal talks with the United National Party (UNP), the Tamil and
Muslim political parties on the proposed reforms.
</P>
<P>
The proposals put forward by the UNP for an independent
election commission and an independent police commission will be
also discussed on the cabinet meeting, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
If the UNP fail to give its approval to the final draft of the
proposed reforms, the government will seek a referendum in March,
1998, they added.
</P>
<P>
The devolution draft, which was proposed in 1995 by President
Kumaratunga, aims at solving the ethnic conflicts between the
Sinhala and the Tamils through a political way.
</P>
<P>
But the Tamil rebels have made it clear that they will not
accept any proposals like this. The rebels have been fighting a
14-year war for an independent country of their own in the
country's northeastern region.
</P>
<P>
The proposals need to win a two-thirds majority in the 225-seat
parliament to be adopted. The UNP, which holds 94 parliament
seats, hasn't expressed its support yet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
