<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPECC Signs 230 Overseas Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 21 (Xinhua) -- China Petroleum Engineering
Construction Corp has signed more than 230 contracts
for foreign engineering and labor services, making itself one of
the 225 largest engineering contractors in the world.
</P>
<P>
The corporation's overseas petroleum engineering projects under
construction involve 1.6 billion US dollars of contracted capital,
compared to 20 million dollars in the early 1990s, according to
today's "China Daily Business Weekly".
</P>
<P>
The CPECC is an affiliate of the China National Petroleum
Corporation. However, it has transformed from a sub-contractor to
a general contractor.
</P>
<P>
CPECC has contracted several petroleum and petrochemical
projects such as an oil refinery and an oil-collecting station in
Kuwait, and oil pipeline in Sudan, an oilfield in Peru and
drilling wells in Mongolia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Besides Asia, CPECC is ready to tap the African and South
American markets, President Qin Anmin said.
</P>
<P>
The corporation has 15 overseas representative offices and 50
agents in more than 20 countries and regions. It has established
business relations with more than 400 foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
The corporation is preparing to evolve into a share-holding
group, which is expected to sharpen its competitiveness in the
global market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Premier Warns People Against Conspiracies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Prime Minister
sheikh Hasina has asked the people and her party workers to face
with patience all conspiracies designed to foil the country's
political stability and economic progress, the independent United
News of Bangladesh (UNB) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Awami League (People's League) is ready to make "more
sacrifices for the country's interest but will not allow any
quarter to play with the nation's destiny," the prime minister was
quoted as saying Saturday at a meeting of the Central Working
Committee of the ruling Awami League.
</P>
<P>
"Conspirators involved in conspiracies against the interest of
the people, and the country will not be tolerated, whatever party
they belong to," she warned.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister advised the League workers to work hard for
the people who would obviously evaluate their work one day.
</P>
<P>
Those who have amassed wealth through illegal means will
certainly face the wrath of the people, the prime minister
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister asked her party leaders and workers to
strengthen the organization by maintaining contacts with the
people, and listen to the people and solve their problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
