<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Aims at Breakthrough in Reform of State Firms, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- China will strive to attain
a breakthrough in the reform of the state-owned enterprise sector
within three years, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, said
China will achieve the target by encouraging the development of
the share-holding system and joint-equity cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 49th meeting of the Interim Committee of the
IMF Board of Governors on the International Monetary System, Dai
said the Chinese government also will take substantial measures
such as merging, bankruptcy and increased diversification of
ownership.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that the Chinese economy has achieved an economic
"soft-landing" and entered a healthy track of high growth and low
inflation through its "steadfast pursuit of moderately tight
macroeconomic policies".
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the real gross domestic product
grew by annualized 9.5 percent, retail price inflation was 4.1
percent over the same period last year, and the balance of
payments position was further strengthened, according to Dai, who
is here to attend the joint annual meetings of the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on September 23-25.
</P>
<P>
"The current favorable macro-economic environment is conducive
to the acceleration of structural reforms," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China will continue to implement moderately
tight fiscal and monetary policies and fine-tune policy stance, so
as to sustain an annual economic growth rate of eight percent and
keep inflation below five percent in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The governor noted that the Chinese government will firmly
implement the basic policy of "One Country, Two Systems," the
Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong with a high degree of
autonomy, to keep Hong Kong's current social and economic systems
unchanged, and basically retain the legal system.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese central government believes that the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) is capable of maintaining the
stability of the Hong Kong dollar which came under speculative
attacks during the recent currency turmoil in Southeast Asia, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the Hong Kong dollar has remained stable, Dai also
stressed that the central government will lend its unstinting
support to the Hong Kong dollar if necessary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Promises More Open to Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will open the door
wider for foreign investment to boost economic recovery, a senior
Thai official said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will also fulfill its commitment to the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) program, Thai Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya
said on Saturday before he was leaving Bangkok for the IMF/World
Bank meeting in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Thanong said that he would tell the same thing at the meeting
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's economic fundamentals remained strong and it was
still an attractive place for foreign investors, he said.
</P>
<P>
To demonstrate its commitment to the IMF program, Thailand's
budget deficit for this fiscal year ending this month would be
capped at 52 billion baht (1.5 billion U.S. dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government also would take measures to curb investment
by the state enterprises and speed up the privatization of several
state enterprises this year.
</P>
<P>
The Thai finance minister also noted that Thailand's bankruptcy
law will be amended to help protect foreign investors who helped
bail out cash-strapped Thai companies.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that the IMF board Saturday agreed to
increase the quotas of member countries' contributions to it by 45
percent, which would raise the IMF's total quota capital to 285
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at giving the fund more resources to provide
help in cases such as the recent crisis in Thailand, the
newspapers added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
