<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Million Italians Rally for National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 20 (Xinhua) -- An estimated one million
Italians flocked to Milan and Venice today for a massive
union-organized demonstration against secession.
</P>
<P>
Buses carrying demonstrators from across Italy poured into
Milan throughout the morning, where organizers said up to one
million had gathered by noon time.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing Communist Refoundation leader Fausto Bertinotti
said the Milan event was "a sacrosanct battle" for national unity.
</P>
<P>
In Venice, where up to 80,000 crowded the central San Marco
Square, Sergion D'Antoni, leader of the Italian Confederation of
Working People's Trade Union called for "more social cohesion in a
united Italy."
</P>
<P>
"I've never seen such a massive demonstration," said Venice
Mayor Massimo Cacciari.
</P>
<P>
Today's demonstrations dwarfed Sunday's Northern League rally
in Venice, which drew only about 15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
During that demonstration, the Northern League leader Umberto
Bossi declared the establishment of his self-styled northern state
of "Padania" and "elections" were planned there next month for
its "parliament."
</P>
<P>
His remarks drew a stern rebuke from Prime Minister Romano
Prodi, who said the separatist party must respect the law.
</P>
<P>
"Today, we see an Italy which knows that the only way to reform
society, the economy and the state is by remaining united," said
Fabio Mussi, a senior member of the Democratic Party of the Left,
the largest party in Italy's central-left governing coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
