<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Banker Calls for Good Economic Fundamentals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Dai Xianglong, governor of
the People's Bank of China, today stressed the need for all the
countries in the world to achieve and sustain good economic
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 49th Meeting of the Interim Committee of the
Board of Governors on the International Monetary System held at
the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center, Dai said that the
exchange rate arrangement in a country should be adapted to its
changing circumstances and realistically there is no universally
uniform exchange rate regime suitable for all countries all the
time.
</P>
<P>
"Regardless of whether a fixed exchange rate regime or a
flexible one is adopted, the most essential challenge facing each
economy is to achieve and sustain its economic fundamentals
through consistently pursuing prudent macroeconomic policies and
improving the soundness of the banking sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese chief banker called on the reserve
currency countries to take account of the external implications in
pursuit of their policy mix and strengthen international policy
coordination, so as to prevent abrupt volatility among major
currency exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon the recent currency turmoil in some Southeast
Asian countries, Dai said: "We believe these instances are of a
temporary nature, their difficulties will soon be overcome, and
confidence will be restored through the strengthened
implementation of a sound economic policy mix and the acceleration
of structural reforms."
</P>
<P>
The cooperation of the international community in general, and
the Asia-Pacific region in particular, has played an important
role in alleviating the turmoil's negative consequences, he said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
