<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Use More Japanese loans for Development of Interior Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 21 (Xinhua) -- More Japanese yen loans will
be introduced to finance the development of China's central and
western regions, a Chinese trade official said.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily Business Weekly quoted Yu Zhensheng, an
official with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, as saying that the trend was line with China's
economic development plan and would benefit both countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Yu, the the 1997 yen loans, worth 203 billion yen
(some 1.68 billion US dollars), will be channeled to 14 projects,
including eight new projects and six expansions, in environmental
protection, agricultural and infrastructure fields in central and
western regions.
</P>
<P>
The projects include Shaanxi Hancheng Power Station, Shanxi
Wangqu Power Station and pollution control for the Xiangjiang
River in Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
China will submit its application for the 1998 yen loans by the
end of this year and his ministry will soon began negotiations
with Japan on the fourth batch of yen loans to China for the next
two years the official said, adding that an agreement is expected
to be reached next year.
</P>
<P>
Japan is one of the first countries to grant governmental loans
to China. In 1979, the country began providing 2,054 billion yen
(16.98 billion dollars) in contracted yen loans, financing some 90
state key projects in transportation, energy, telecommunications,
water supply and other infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
China had a good foreign debt repayment record and its ability
to return foreign debts was unquestionable, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
