<HEADLINE> More Ethnic Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A total of 53 members of the
Kayin National Union (KNU), the largest remaining anti-government
ethnic armed group in Myanmar, surrendered this month to the
government in Dawei area, Tanintharyi division, official paper The
New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
Those who "exchanged arms for peace" included 43 members led by
commandant U Soe Wai and 10 others led by Saw Shar Bi.
</P>
<P>
The two groups brought in a total of 57 assorted arms and 1,921
rounds of ammunition, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The KNU, one of the 16 ethnic armed groups in Myanmar, has been
active on the Myanmar-Thai border in armed opposition to the
government. It is also the last group which has not made peace
with the government although four rounds of peace talks have been
held.  
</P>
</TEXT>
