<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Currency Crisis Not Affecting China's Financial Market: Economist (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unlike the Southeast Asian countries, which suffered declining
exports as a result of pegging their national currencies to the US
dollar and were later compelled to practise free exchange rate,
China has wisely chosen to open its foreign exchange market
gradually.
</P>
<P>
China's prudence in reforming its foreign exchange system, its
robust economic growth, and reforms in other sectors have combined
to contribute to a stable exchange rate of the yuan, Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
Large foreign investment and debts, especially short-term
debts, have put some Southeast nations under great pressure to
repay interest, according to the professor.
</P>
<P>
China has no problem in debt repayment as its foreign debts are
appropriate in size and structure and are properly used, Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
An increasing macro-economic control ability, he added, is
another reason why China can effectively resist the spillovers of
financial instability on the international markets.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government is in control of the economic
lifelines and the major financial institutions, and its great power
in economic macro control is unparalleled by the governments of
the Southeast Asian nations," Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
As a lesson to learn from the currency crisis in Southeast
Asia, China should create a good and favorable macro environment
for the financial market by maintaining a stable economic growth
and avoiding big ups and downs in economic development, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that China should adhere to a rational policy on
use of foreign investment so as to prevent any possible assault on
the financial market by short-term speculative capital from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
To reduce financial risks, the reform in the foreign exchange
system should go ahead gradually and financial supervision should
be further strengthened, Economist Xiao said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
