<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, September 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Premier Li Peng arrived here from Beijing by air
Saturday afternoon to attend the World Bank/International Monetary
Fund (IMF) Annual Meetings scheduled for September 23-25.
</P>
<P>
As head of government of the host country, Li is to deliver a
speech at the opening ceremony of the meetings on September
23. (Hong Kong-Li Peng-Arrival)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran has condemned the United States of recent
nuclear test while hindering peaceful use of atomic energy in
Iran, Iran's official news agency IRNA said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a statement by the Foreign Ministry spokesman
Mahmoud Mohammadi Friday night as saying that the U.S. had been
blocking peaceful measures supervised by the International Atomic
Energy Agency (IAEA) while that country had itself been conducting
destructive atomic tests. (Iran-Nuclear-USA)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- About five billion Rand (1.1 billion
U.S. Dollars) in gold bullion were being stolen a year in South
Africa, local daily Saturday Star reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Estimates of the amount of gold stolen from all the mines vary
between 10 and 15 percent of the total production. It was
affecting the viability of the mines, mine managers were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"If South Africa's gold mines could produce 10 percent more per
annum, we could probably employ 80,000 more miners," James Watt, a
metallurgist, said. (Safrica-Theft In Gold Mines)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Fourteen people were killed in a helicopter crash in
southern Thailand late Friday night, local media reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the dead, including many high-ranking military
officers, were airlifted to Bangkok earlier Saturday and Thai
Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh and other top Thai military
officers went to the airport to assess the situation.
</P>
<P>
The Thai military helicopter reportedly was carrying 21 people
who escorted Thai Queen Sirikit Kittiyakara to inspect southern
Thailand when it crashed. (Thailand-Helicopter-Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos said Saturday that
he will step down when his term ends next year and "will not run
for re-election."
</P>
<P>
Ramos made the promise upon his arrival in General Santos city,
the Southern Philippines, from a 10-day, four-nation visit.
</P>
<P>
"I am fully satisfied with having served as your president for
one six-year term as mandated in the constitution," President
Ramos said. (Philippines-Politics)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Some 200,000 Iranian army
soldiers staged a counter-offensive war game against chemical
attacks on Friday, the fourth day of military maneuvers, near
Qom, 150 kilometers south of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's Persian daily Jomhuri Islami reported that the
armored and mechanized rangers of the army repelled the chemical
attacks by the hypothetical enemy and cleared the area of chemical
contamination during the war games. (Iran-Maneuvers-Chemical)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Former Secretary-General of Namibia's ruling
Southwest African People's Organization (SWAPO) Moses Garoeb has
died in Windhoek after a long illness, President Sam Nujoma
announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Garoeb, 52, died at the Windhoek state hospital on Friday. He
had been suffering from diabetes and high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma announced that flags would be flown at half mast from
Sunday. A state funeral, the first of its kind since Namibia's
independence in 1990, was being arranged. (Namibia-SWAPO Chief
Dies) 
</P>
</TEXT>
