<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Currency Crisis Not Affecting China's Financial Market: Economist (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The recent currency crisis in
some Southeast Asian nations will not affect China's financial
market as well as its efforts to push forward reforms in the
foreign exchange system, noted economist Xiao Zhuoji said.
</P>
<P>
"We should learn a lesson from the crisis and not blindly
pursue capital-account convertibility before conditions are mature,
but our efforts to reform the foreign exchange system should not
be delayed," Xiao, a professor at Beijing University, told Xinhua
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
He said that because of different national conditions, the
recent financial turbulence in Southeast Asia will not affect
China's financial market and the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
The currency crisis first started in Thailand in July when the
Baht plunged against the US dollar and stock prices plummeted,
forcing overseas investors to bail out. The crisis later spread to
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy, though small in per capita terms, is
powerful enough to resist any residual effects from the currency
volatility in Southeast Asia, Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
China reported an annual gross domestic product of more than
800 billion US dollars in 1996 and its year-end foreign exchange
reserves exceeded 120 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
A major cause of the currency crisis in Southeast Asia,
according to Xiao, is imbalance in economic structure, lack of
diversity in exports and excessive dependence on the international
market.
</P>
<P>
Conversely, China has a relatively balanced economic structure
and diversified export and domestic markets, which make it less
reliant on the international market, Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
"This has enabled China to resist the adverse influence from
overseas economies," the economist said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that in sharp contrast to huge current-account
deficits of some Southeast Asian nations, China has enjoyed
surplus in the balance of international payments under both the
current and capital accounts since an overhaul of the foreign
exchange system in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970921.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 </DATE_TIME>
